<HEAD>Shares Open Firm, Trading Active</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices opened firmer Wednesday on reports that Chinese troops responsible for the slaughter of pro-democracy demonstrators were leaving <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Brokers said trading was active, but investors remained cautious awaiting further developments. The Hang Seng Index of blue chips, which plummeted on Monday to its worst loss since the worldwide market collapse in 1987, gained about 140 points to 2,289 within the first hour of trading. Before the morning session, members of the <ORGANIZATION> Hong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kong </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Stock </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION> stood for three minutes of silence tribute to victims of the military attack Sunday, in which hundreds and perhaps thousands were killed. On Monday, the index closed at 2,093.61 points, down 581.77 points from Friday. The drop was the worst since the 1987 international market collapse, when the index fell 1,120.99 points.
