<HEAD>Hong Kong Share Prices Plummet, Protesters March</HEAD>
<HEAD>EDS: LEADS with 11 grafs to UPDATE with Tuesday figures. Pick up
12th pvs, `In nearby...'</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto HK2</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HONG KONG (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Share prices opened lower Tuesday in nervous reaction to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s military crackdown on pro-democracy demonstrators, and thousands of residents staged funeral processions for slain protesters. The developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> have focused new public attention on the accord under which the British colony will revert to Chinese rule in 1997. Officials reported a run on some China-owned banks Monday in withdrawals aimed at protesting the Chinese military's killings of hundreds and perhaps thousands of unarmed protesters in efforts to quell a popular uprising in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Thousands of angry <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> residents gathered outside the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, the mainland government's de facto embassy in the territory. Governor Sir <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> also met <PERSON> Xu </PERSON> <PERSON> Jiatun </PERSON>, head of the agency, to express his concern over the brutal force used, the government reported without giving details. <PERSON> Wilson </PERSON> originally was to leave Monday for <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> to discuss <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s future with members of the <ORGANIZATION> British </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commons </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> ' </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foreign </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>. He delayed his departure to Wednesday because of the developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. In <LOCATION> London </LOCATION>, some lawmakers called for a reconsideration of the agreement. But British Foreign Secretary <PERSON> Geoffrey </PERSON> <PERSON> Howe </PERSON> reaffirmed <LOCATION> Britain </LOCATION>'s agreement to the accord. Under a Chinese-British agreement signed in 1984, <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> has said the territory can maintain its capitalistic lifestyle under a `` one country, two systems'' concept run by <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> people without <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> interference. <PERSON> Ming </PERSON> <PERSON> Pao </PERSON>, a Chinese-language daily respected for its <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> coverage, said a young guard fired four shots at Chinese Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> in the Great Hall of the People on Sunday and the premier was hit in the thigh. He was not seriously injured, and the guard was killed, the newspaper reported. The Hang Seng Index of blue chips, which plummeted on Monday to its worst loss since the worldwide market collapse in 1987, fell about 70 points shortly after the market opened Tuesday, but rebounded within an hour to 2,075 points. On Monday, the index closed at 2,093.61 points, down 581.77 points from Friday. The drop was the worst since the 1987 international market collapse, when the index fell 1,120.99 points. In nearby <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION>, the weighted stock market index dropped 455.44 points to close at 9,120.54, the largest single-day loss in the market's 27-year history. Real estate specialists in <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> said property values could fall 15 to 20 percent unless the Chinese situation stabilizes. `` This is the worst scenario come to pass,'' said real estate executive <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Varty </PERSON>. `` Over the past few weeks everyone has been looking at how this matter will be played out, and this bloodshed is the worst possible way.'' Monetary Affairs Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Nendick </PERSON> urged investors to remain calm and cautioned a run on mainland banks could reflect adversely on the territory's status as the world's third financial center after <LOCATION> London </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>. Some banks said their rate of withdrawal was 30 percent higher than usual, but no figures were available. `` I think they have gone mad,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Lee </PERSON>, an outspoken member of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislative </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>. `` I believe it -LRB- the military crackdown -RRB- is the work by a group of very old men who want to cling to their power and are prepared to sacrifice thousands and millions of lives.'' Protesters continued the rallies held daily to support the democracy movement since martial law was imposed May 20. On Monday, about 3,000 Catholics and Protestants marched past the <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> office in a funeral procession for the dead. About 98 percent of <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>'s population of 5.7 million are Chinese, and two-thirds are refugees from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> or their descendants.
