<HEAD>Storm Dot Hits Central Philippines</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Tropical storm Dot hit the central <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> today with heavy rain and 47 mph winds, officials said. There were no immediate reports of damage or casualties. Chief weather forecaster <PERSON> Eduardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Parong </PERSON> said the center of the storm came ashore at the southern tip of <LOCATION> Samar </LOCATION> island, about 410 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. The storm was moving west northwest at 14 mph, he said. A weather bulletin said the storm, the third to hit the <LOCATION> Philippines </LOCATION> this year, dumped rain over a wide area stretching from <LOCATION> Bataan </LOCATION> province west of <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> across <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bay </LOCATION> to northern <LOCATION> Mindanao </LOCATION>. The coast guard said it prevented ships from leaving various ports. There were no reports of damage or casualties from <LOCATION> Samar </LOCATION> or the neighboring island of <LOCATION> Leyte </LOCATION>, which also lay in the storm's path. Such reports take days to reach the capital because of poor communications.
