<SECOND>PM-Walesa,0777</SECOND>
<HEAD>Walesa Sends Letter to Bush, Emphasizes Coming Challenges</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Poland, Bjt ^An AP Extra</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN COSTELLOE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GDANSK, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As the scope of Solidarity's massive election victory became clear, <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> sent some advice to his friend President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>: keep promoting investment in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>. Then, the shipyard electrician who rallied a restless people to challenge the Communist system got into his blue <ORGANIZATION> Volkswagen </ORGANIZATION> van on Monday afternoon and drove off down the streets of this proud port city. International labor hero <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> still retains a host of folksy touches nearly nine years after strikes at the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION> that spawned Solidarity catapulted him to fame and a Nobel Peace prize. He walked with wife, <PERSON> Danuta </PERSON>, and 19-year-old son, <PERSON> Bogdan </PERSON>, to cast his ballot at city polling station No. 169 in Sunday's historic elections A young woman outside the polling station gave him a red rose and praised his tireless efforts. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> replied with a smile: `` Well, I did n't do all this just for myself.'' Like many busy men wrapped up in their work, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has trouble taking time off. `` We hope you can go on vacation. You deserve it,'' the Rev. <PERSON> Henryk </PERSON> <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>, a close adviser, told him as 3,000 people cheered outside <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brygida </LOCATION>'s church. `` We hope you can go to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' Only half of <PERSON> Jankowski </PERSON>'s wish is officially scheduled now: <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> is heading to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> this fall for a speech to the <ORGANIZATION> AFL-CIO </ORGANIZATION> and most likely another meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>. In fact, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> is heading over to the <LOCATION> Walesas </LOCATION>' for lunch next month. There, the president will sit down to a traditional Polish meal with the 45-year-old <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>, his wife and at least some of the couple's eight children in a pleasant residential area outside central <LOCATION> Gdansk </LOCATION>. `` This is a rehearsal for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s visit,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said with a hearty laugh as he acted as host at a private party on election eve at his single-family home on 54 Polanki Street. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> will sit at a plain wooden table, surrounded by paintings of nature scenes and religious motifs. When <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> shows <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> into the living room, the president will see a picture of Pope <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> on the wall. `` My highest authority'' is the way <PERSON> Roman </PERSON> <PERSON> Catholic </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> refers to his Polish-born hero and mentor in the <LOCATION> Vatican </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> met when <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> as vice president visited <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> in 1987. A photograph of the two conferring adorns the wall outside <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>'s office in the gritty local headquarters of Solidarity two blocks from the shipyard. Like any folk hero, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> has his trademarks _ the handle-bar mustache, the Solidarity badge, the <PERSON> Black </PERSON> <PERSON> Madonna </PERSON> of Czestochowa pin on his lapel. Less well-known is his bluntness. On Monday, the labor federation leader, wearing a blue sportcoat, bulldozed through reporters seeking a statement from him on election results. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said the voting shows Poles want `` very big reforms'' but also cautioned `` we have to keep searching further'' to solve the nation's woes. Then he bounded up the steps back into the <LOCATION> St. </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Brygida </LOCATION>'s rectory to cap a victory he has been seeking along with his larger successes: assuring the future of the <ORGANIZATION> Lenin </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Shipyard </ORGANIZATION>. In what he called an act of providence, Polish-born American multimillionaire <PERSON> Barbara </PERSON> <PERSON> Piasecka-Johnson </PERSON> stepped in with a promise of a huge investment to rescue the ailing yard from a government-ordered shutdown. After lunch with Mrs. <PERSON> Piasecka-Johnson </PERSON>, her advisers and members of the Communist-picked shipyard management Monday, <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> used the occasion to promote the next phase of his cause: reform of <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s faltering and often chaotic economy `` All our political victories will mean nothing if we do n't improve the economy,'' said <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> faces constant shortages of consumer goods, spare parts and food items. Many Poles disillusioned with the country's plight seek work in <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>, the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> and elsewhere. To ease the situation, <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has been seeking to attract foreign investment. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration recently began leading the cheers for <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s success in that area. `` What Mrs. <PERSON> Piasecka-Johnson </PERSON> is doing is a continuation of what President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> has already told us,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said in reference to <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> administration support for Polish economic reforms. `` She is fulfilling it immediately.'' `` So I am sending a personal letter through her to the president in which I thank him for wanting to meet <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> halfway,'' <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> then handed Mrs. <PERSON> Piasecka-Johnson </PERSON> a plain white envelope containing the letter for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, as news photographers' cameras clicked and TV cameras