<HEAD>GAO Clears VA Official, Agency Says</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> has concluded that the chief medical officer of the <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> did not try to improperly dictate the outcome of a study of death rates in VA hospitals, an agency spokesman said Monday night. However, the study does conclude that expressions of concern by Dr. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Gronvall </PERSON> over the impact of such a study on the VA image `` led some people to believe'' he was giving such instructions, said <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Affairs </ORGANIZATION>, successor to the VA.. Sen. <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Cranston </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Veterans </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>, asked for the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> investigation after <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported last October that <PERSON> Gronvall </PERSON> had ordered a change in methodology to lower the percentage of VA hospitals showing abnormal death The newspaper reported results of the study in Tuesday editions. The telephone number listed for the author of the study was answered by someone who said he no longer lives there. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said he had seen a copy of the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> report earlier in the day. <PERSON> Gronvall </PERSON> was traveling and could not be reached, but judging by his letter to <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> contained in the report commenting in the findings, `` I think he feels somewhat vindicated,'' said <PERSON> Smith </PERSON>. The dispute arose when another VA staff member, the late Dr. <PERSON> Francis </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Conrad </PERSON>, argued in memos that chaging the study methods could be seen as `` self serving.'' The issue is what statistical cut-off to use in judging whether death rates are within the normal range of variation. Only six of the <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION>'s 172 hospitals _ 3.5 percent _ would be judged to have abnormal death rates if the analyst wants to be 99 percent sure that the determination is not the result of normal fluctations. But if the analyst wants to be 95 percent sure, 12 hospitals or 7 percent would be judged to have abnormal death rates. VA began the study after the <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Care </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Financing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> found that 2.5 percent of the nation's private hospitals had abnormally high death rates. <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> VA </ORGANIZATION> and the financing agency kept records differently and the percentages arrived at by the two studies could not be compared. The Veterans Department plans to release its study next week using both statistical cutoffs, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> said.
