<HEAD>Railroad, Pipeline Company Agree on Community Reparations</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN BERNARDINO, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A railroad and a fuel-shipping company announced plans Monday to reimburse residents of a neighborhood stricken by twin disasters last month. The deal outlines community reparations, promises $ 5,000 for each family evacuated, assures residents that the site is safe and calls for a study of utilities in the area. For the <ORGANIZATION> Calnev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pipe </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Line </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, the agreement cleared city objections to plans to replace its 14-inch diameter petroleum fuel line, which exploded in a deadly fireball on May 25, about two weeks after a <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> train derailed on May 12. Four people, including two residents were killed in the derailment, and two residents were killed in the pipeline explosion. Dozens more were injured in the explosion. <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Safety </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> investigators have focused on the possibility that the out-of-control freight damaged the nearby pipeline as it vaulted from the tracks. The plan was announced jointly by city officials, executives of <LOCATION> Calnev </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Southern </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Pacific </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> and <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> of <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>. ` No court would have ordered them to do what they've agreed to do today,'' City Attorney <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Penman </PERSON> said. `` The question now is whether this is going to be finalized.'' One of the things city officials had sought was immediate assistance for displaced families, and <PERSON> Penman </PERSON> said, `` that $ 5,000 reimbursement really helps.'' The $ 5,000 is to be paid to each family that returns to their home. Calnev officials said the payments, estimated to total about $ 750,000, would begin Wednesday. `` What the agreement is today is a first crack at getting started,'' said <PERSON> Anthony </PERSON> <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Andrukaitis </PERSON>, vice president of <ORGANIZATION> GATX </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Terminals </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Calnev </PERSON>'s corporate owner. `` It is nowhere near a comprehensive settlement.'' The companies tentatively agreed to reimburse the city for overtime paid for police, fire and other emergency personnel, continue to pay for housing and meals for displaced families and to buy the homes that were destroyed or severely damaged. The new pipeline will buried at least six feet deep, twice the federal standard and covered with concrete for 600 feet, the length of the rail disaster area, <PERSON> Andrukaitis </PERSON> said. `` If we can get the new line in by Wednesday, we'd test it Thursday and possibly be operating by Friday,'' <PERSON> Andrukaitis </PERSON> said. Mayor <PERSON> W.R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Holcomb </PERSON> said Monday that 95 homes out of the 178 that were evacuated would be immediately reopened for residents' return. `` All the environmental and safety experts agree on the safety and integrity of the area,'' <PERSON> Holcomb </PERSON> said. The city attorney emphasized <PERSON> Calnev </PERSON>'s support for a federal study of the placement of gasoline, natural gas pipelines and other vital utilities in the greater <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION> area. If the study recommends moving the <LOCATION> Calnev </LOCATION> fuel line, the company has agreed to do it, <PERSON> Penman </PERSON> said. The proposed engineering study would examine the sort of juxtaposition that apparently played a role in the double disasters.
