<BYLINE>By DAVE SKIDMORE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 House members have flooded the Rules Committee with more than 100 proposed amendments to savings and loan bailout legislation, dimming the chances of floor action this week. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration, which announced its <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L proposal on Feb. 6 and challenged <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> to act within 45 days, has shown increasing impatience with the pace of action in the House. The Rules Committee, chaired by Rep. <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Moakley </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Massachusetts </LOCATION>, the ranking Democrat after the death last week of former chairman <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, is scheduled to consider the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation on Tuesday. It will decide which amendments will be considered by the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> when it takes up <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L legislation written by the Banking, Judiciary and Ways and Means panels. House Majority Leader <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, D-Wash., told <PERSON> Moakley </PERSON> last week that he wants the Rules panel to finish work Tuesday so the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> can take up the bill on Wednesday However, nearly 50 <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members have asked to speak to the Rules Committee and the panel must wade through more than 109 amendments, a difficult task to achieve in one day. If the <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> finished work Wednesday, the full <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> could begin debate on Thursday, but, since the chamber is out of session on Friday, any vote likely would be delayed until next week. `` The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> passed this thing on April 19 and the losses -LRB- in S & amp; Ls -RRB- have grown by over $ 500 million since that date,'' said Assistant Treasury Secretary <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> W. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON>. The industry `` is just hemorrhaging out there and every day they delay passage costs at least $ 10 million,'' he said. More than half a dozen of the amendments under consideration would weaken what the administration considers the key change in the bill _ a requirement that <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L owners invest at least $ 3 in tangible or `` real money'' capital for every $ 100 in lending. A high capital level acts as a buffer, absorbing losses before federal deposit insurance kicks in. Rep. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON>, D-Ill., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Banking </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Subcommittee </ORGANIZATION> on Financial Institutions, had planned to offer an amendment that would allow regulators, at their discretion, to count `` supervisory goodwill'' as tangible capital, but pulled back after the administration decided to oppose it The <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> reported in Tuesday editions that Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Tenn </LOCATION>., planned to urge the Rules Committee to allow the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to vote on an amendment that would weaken restrictions on counting goodwill as tangible capital It said the measure would benefit several hundred S & amp; Ls, including <ORGANIZATION> Heritage </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Kingsport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, where <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON> has at least $ 200,000 on deposit. <PERSON> Wendell </PERSON> <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON>, chief executive of the <ORGANIZATION> S </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; L, was quoted by the newspaper as saying that without the amendment the institution would have to come up with cash to replace $ 28 million in goodwill it currently counts as capital. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> was quoted as saying he asked <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON> to sponsor the measure. <PERSON> Kirk </PERSON> said the amendment's effect on <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON> would be minimal, perhaps $ 250, and added: `` If you try to pin a conflict on him it would be criminal. It would be low down.'' <PERSON> Quillen </PERSON> was quoted as saying: `` In my mind, there is no conflict'' of interest. Efforts to reach him by telephone Monday night were unsuccessful. Supervisory goodwill is an accounting break offered by regulators in the early 1980s to institutions that took ailing S & amp; Ls off the government's hands. <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> argues that it is unfair to penalize S & amp; Ls who took the accounting break at the government's urging. However, the administration argues that it is unfair to taxpayers to allow the institutions with supervisory goodwill to operate with none of their owners' money at risk. <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> and other <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> members from <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>, including Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>, met with <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> officials last Thursday in attempt to secure the administration's support for their compromise amendment However, <PERSON> Mullins </PERSON> said the proposal `` is simply not acceptable to us.'' As an alternate, <PERSON> Annunzio </PERSON> will back an amendment by Rep. <PERSON> Henry </PERSON> <PERSON> Hyde </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-Ill </LOCATION>., that would permit institutions with goodwill to use administrative appeals to delay the imposition of tougher capital rules for up to 18 months Other amendments before the Rules Committee would, if permitted to reach the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, reopen virtually every major battle already fought in the committees that wrote the bill. Several amendments would delete provisions designed to help provide housing to poor people. Others would weaken the requirement that the S & amp; L industry contribute $ 300 million a year to pay interest on government bailout borrowing.
