<HEAD>Bush's China Experience Shaping US Policy</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TOM RAUM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> once suggested that the more he learned about the Chinese the less he understood them. Now, his experience in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is a guiding influence in setting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy toward the troubled giant. In his announcement Monday of a cutoff in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> arms sales to protest the bloody suppression of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s pro-democracy movement, the government's No. 1 <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> hand said he took the action because he understands <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> `` reasonably well.'' For that reason, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said the events of the past few days could only leave him with `` a saddened heart.'' `` I am trying to take steps that will encourage a peaceful change, and yet recognize the fact that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> does have a great pride in its own history. And my recommendations are based on my knowledge of Chinese history,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. That does n't mean he understands what has happened, said <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who less than four months ago shook hands with bicyclists in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, presented <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> cowboy boots to Prime Minister <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> and bantered about exercise regimens with senior leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON>. Of the military assault that left hundreds dead and thousands wounded, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said: `` I condemn it; I do n't try to explain it.'' Asked for his best assessment of the political situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> also demurred. `` It's too obscure,'' he said at a news conference Monday. But <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> expertise has always been a major element of the well-laden foreign-policy resume that <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> brought to the Oval Office. For <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, who headed the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> liaison office in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> for 16 months in 1974-75 and since then has visited the nation five times, this expertise is also the source of extreme caution _ a caution that previously provoked criticism. In his 1987 pre-election autobiography, `` Looking Forward,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> wrote that during his tour of duty in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> he often had the `` feeling the more you learn about the Chinese, the less you really understand them.'' `` I have a special affection for the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> people. I've kept up my knowledge of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and my relationship with various leaders there,'' he told a business audience Monday night. Although <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> leaders of both parties were near unanimous in their praise for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s stern but careful actions Monday, his reticence in speaking out for human rights when he visited <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> in late February prompted criticism. The criticism intensified when a dissident he invited to a farewell banquet, astrophysicist <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON>, was barred by Chinese police from attending the ceremony. Still, <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> defended this caution anew on Monday while issuing his strongest criticism thus far of the Chinese government. `` This is not a time for anything other than a prudent, reasoned response,'' he said. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said his actions Monday will deny the Chinese more than $ 600 million worth of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> government military equipment sales and an estimated $ 85 million or so annually in private arms sales. He also banned visits by <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> military officials, offered humanitarian and medical assistance to those wounded in the assault and suggested that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would extend the visas of Chinese students here afraid to return to their homeland. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, however, said he was not ready to do `` something more flamboyant,'' such as recommend trade sanctions or recall the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador, `` because I happen to believe that this relationship is vital to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> suggested, as he has in the past, that he's sensitive to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s own sensitivity to outside criticism. `` <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> historically has been less than totally interested in what other countries think of their performance,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. Still, he expressed hope that `` the depth of the feeling towards democracy is so great that you ca n't put the genie back in the bottle and return to total repression.'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s actions won support from many on <LOCATION> Capitol </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Hill </LOCATION>. `` This is a time to allow the president to lead on that kind of issue, especially when you have a president with this level of personal expertise in Chinese affairs,'' said Sen. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Boren </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Okla </LOCATION>., chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Intelligence </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION>
</TEXT>
