<HEAD>Appeals Court Rules Topeka Schools Allowed Desegregation to Falter</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with two grafs to RECAST; PICKS UP 3rd graf pvs, `The
case ...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN HANNA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOPEKA, Kan. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Vestiges of school segregation remain in <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> 35 years after it lost the <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> vs. <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Education </ORGANIZATION> decision, which paved the way for desegregation of schools nationwide, a federal appeals court ruled. The 10th <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> panel's decision, made available Monday, reversed a ruling that would have closed the case that found `` separate but equal'' schools for blacks and whites unconstitutional. The case was reopened 10 years ago by parents who said <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>'s schools were still segregated `` We won,'' said <PERSON> Rich </PERSON> <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>, an attorney representing the parents of 17 black schoolchildren. `` We feel that 10 years of work was not in vain. We feel vindicated by the decision. It's been quite a long time coming.'' The group involved in the lawsuit included parent <PERSON> Linda </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>, who was a student when her name went on the original lawsuit. `` My first reaction was shock, then I was pleased, very pleased,'' said <PERSON> Cheryl </PERSON> <PERSON> Brown </PERSON> <PERSON> Henderson </PERSON>, <PERSON> Buckner </PERSON>'s sister. `` I believe that the case showed that there is a lot of educational enhancement that is not taking place here.'' In its decision published in <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> on Friday, the panel rejected <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> District Judge <PERSON> Richard </PERSON> <PERSON> Rogers </PERSON>' contention in April 1987 that parents of minority students had to prove a pattern of intentional discrimination to force the district to come up with a plan for more racially balanced schools. `` Because we are convinced that <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> has not sufficiently countered the effects of both the momentum of its pre-Brown segregation and its subsequent segregative acts in the 1960s, we reverse,'' the appeals court said. The judges also reversed a lower court ruling that the <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> school district had not violated Title VI of the Civil Rights Act of 1964. <PERSON> Gary </PERSON> <PERSON> Sebelius </PERSON>, an attorney for the the school district, said officials were awaiting receipt of the dissenting opinion in the 2-1 ruling before deciding whether to appeal. He added that the ruling confirmed the high quality of <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>'s schools `` Throughout their decision they note that <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> offers excellent educational opportunities to all its students, wherever they be,'' <PERSON> Sebelius </PERSON> said. `` There was absolutely no hint or contest of the quality education the district provides.'' The court noted that neither the school district nor the <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> community was actively resisting desegregation, and cited the national recognition of the district's innovative curriculum. `` This active engagement has largely been directed at concerns other than desegregation, however,'' the appeals court said. `` For the most part, the <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> school district has exercised a form of benign neglect.'' The original class-action lawsuit challenged the constitutionality of a <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION> law authorizing school segregation. The May 17, 1954, <ORGANIZATION> Supreme </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> decision paved the way for nationwide school desegregation and busing. <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> schools were required to submit an integration plan, which was approved in 1955. In 1979, the case was revived by black parents who claimed <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> had failed to desegregate its schools. <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION> found the school district to be integrated and unified. Local officials of the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> for the Advancement of Colored People at the time blasted <ORGANIZATION> Rogers </ORGANIZATION>' decision, saying blacks could not get a fair hearing because of racism in <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION>. The appeals court ruled that the district's policy of permitting students to attend neighborhood schools was insufficient to desegregate schools because neighborhoods are still racially segregated. <LOCATION> Topeka </LOCATION> is 90 percent white. There are about 14,000 students in the city school district.
