<HEAD>Jury Selected As Abortion Demonstration Trial Takes Center Stage</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAMPA, Fla. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The judge sat center stage, the defendants took up the orchestra, mezzanine and balcony and a defense attorney asked potential jurors if they'd ever had an abortion. Set in a 300-seat theater, the drama was real as 155 anti-abortion activists went on trial Monday for trespassing during a protest at a clinic April 15. The judge had to rent the hall intended for nightclub acts and jazz ensembles because no local courtroom was big enough. `` Here in the first row,'' attorney <PERSON> B. </PERSON> <PERSON> Larry </PERSON> <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> asked before a jury of six was selected, `` has anyone had an abortion?'' When a prosecutor objected, <PERSON> Smith </PERSON> asked whether any of the 95 prospective jurors knew of anyone who had had an abortion. About half said yes. More than 180 people were arrested and charged with trespassing during the protest organized by Operation Rescue. The charge carries up to a year in jail and a $ 1,000 fine. Some pleaded no contest and received six months' probation. Judge <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Arnold </PERSON> merged the cases and rented a theater at the <ORGANIZATION> Tampa </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Performing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Center </ORGANIZATION> complex for about $ 5,000 for what is expected to be a weeklong trial. `` We're not here to determine the issue of abortion,'' said Assistant State Attorney <PERSON> Hank </PERSON> <PERSON> Lavandera </PERSON>, standing before a stage set up with a makeshift judge's bench. `` You are being selected to serve on a jury, not on a legislative delegation,'' he said. `` What I'm concerned with is if you can set aside your own preconceptions and follow the law.''
