<SECOND>PM-China at a Glance,0603</SECOND>
<HEAD>Summary of Developments in China</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> today:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>RIVAL ARMY FACTIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Armies loyal to rival political factions were reported battling for control of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Soldiers of the 28th Army, believed loyal to ousted <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> leader <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, exchanged fire with the <ORGANIZATION> 27th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, which invaded central <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> Saturday night to crush the pro-democracy movement. A soldier of the Beijing-based <ORGANIZATION> 38th </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> said it was fired upon by the 27th on the west side of the city. The 27th has been fortifying positions around <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>. Hundreds of soldiers were seen along the airport road and a main highway in northeastern <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Residents said the troops, from the northeast city of <LOCATION> Shenyang </LOCATION>, were `` not shooting at the people.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OFFICIAL CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced that nearly 300 people had been killed and more than 7,000 injured and said the figure included soldiers, `` thugs,'' bystanders and 23 students. The official figures were far lower than unofficial estimates of more than 500 deaths.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>LI SHOOTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 A young guard reportedly shot four times at Premier <PERSON> Li </PERSON> <PERSON> Peng </PERSON> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>'s Great Hall of the People on Sunday, slightly wounding him in the thigh. The guard was immediately killed, according to the report in a <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> daily. <PERSON> Li </PERSON> has not been seen in public since May 25, five days after he declared martial law.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DENIAL OF DENG'S DEATH</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The government denied a report from <LOCATION> Taiwan </LOCATION> that leader <PERSON> Deng </PERSON> <PERSON> Xiaoping </PERSON> had died, calling it a `` fabrication designed to make people uneasy and create chaos.'' <PERSON> Deng </PERSON>, 84, has been out of sight since May 16 and there were reports he was hospitalized for treatment of prostate cancer.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER REPORTS OF FIGHTING</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 A contingent of soldiers fired directly on a crowd near a major intersection west of <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION>, a foreign witness said. The witness heard screams from the crowd, but did not know if anyone was hit. Another source said tanks were moving north and firing near the university area in northwestern <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Soldiers at some intersections have fired at any passing vehicles. Unidentified people opened fire from a window on soldiers and tanks outside the military museum in western <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, a witness said. Some students and other civilians are known to have captured weapons from soldiers over the weekend.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>BEIJING AT STANDSTILL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 People hoarded food, public transportation was at a halt and many people did not go to work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>DEMONSTRATIONS IN OTHER CITIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-government demonstrations have spread to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nanjing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> and numerous other cities. <ORGANIZATION> Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Radio </ORGANIZATION> said student-led barricading of streets `` had brought the whole municipal economy to the brink of collapse.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>FOREIGNERS IN CHINA</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Foreign embassies, including the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> mission, urged their nationals to leave and some arranged special charter flights to speed evacuation. Hundreds of anxious foreigners jammed airline offices and swamped embassy switchboards with telephone calls. Several thousand filled the international departure area of <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>. Several <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have accelerated a withdrawal of expatriates from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Chrysler </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Boeing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> were among companies that said they had evacuated people because of the violence and uncertainty elsewhere in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. Some companies far from the violence said they had no plans to move staff, and that operations were normal.
</TEXT>
