<HEAD>Maximum Sentences Given To Two Convicted In Policeman's Murder</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RAYNER PIKE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two narcotics dealers who murdered a rookie policeman _ allegedly on orders from a drug lord _ were sentenced to the maximum 25 years to life in prison today as more than 100 police officers cheered. A third dealer received the same sentence May 16 for his role in the 1988 death of <PERSON> Edward </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, whose slaying outside the home of a drug witness became an issue in the White House campaign and a battle cry for law enforcement. Justice <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Demakos </PERSON>, in sentencing <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON> and <PERSON> Todd </PERSON> <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, recommended that neither receive parole. Neither Cobb, 25, nor <PERSON> Scott </PERSON>, 20, addressed the judge. <PERSON> Demakos </PERSON> promised, as he did at the sentencing of co-defendant <PERSON> Philip </PERSON> <PERSON> Copeland </PERSON>, that his last act as a judge would be to remind the parole board of his recommendation. He labeled the pair `` unfit to live in society.'' <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, 22, was shot five times in the head at close range while he sat in a patrol car guarding the home of a drug witness. Prosecutors charged that the officer was killed on orders from alleged drug lord <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> `` Pappy'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> in retaliation for his jailing on a weapons charge. <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> has not been charged in the slaying and has denied involvement. The slaying gained widespread attention during the White House campaign when <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>'s father, <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON>, presented his son's badge to <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, saying he supported him because of <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s support of the death penalty. <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrne </PERSON>, a former police officer, left the courtroom without comment today. The sentencing of <PERSON> Scott </PERSON> and <PERSON> Cobb </PERSON> was postponed last month while prosecutors tried unsuccessfully to persuade the two to provide evidence against <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>. A fourth defendant, alleged triggerman <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> McClary </PERSON>, is on trial in the slaying.
</TEXT>
