<HEAD>Khomeini Supporters Shut Down West Beirut, Shiite Areas</HEAD>
<HEAD>With PM-Iran-Khomeini, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Mourners bewailing the death of Iranian patriarch <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> brought west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> to a standstill today, but did not stop Christians and Syrians from exchanging salvos of shellfire. Police said four Christian and five Druse Moslem civilians were wounded in sporadic overnight shelling duels that ended before dawn. In an unrelated incident, gunmen shot and killed a Palestinian employee of the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Relief </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Works </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> in Syrian-policed west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> early today, police said. A police spokesman said <PERSON> Nafez </PERSON> <PERSON> Awdeh </PERSON> `` died instantly and the gunmen sped away in a green <ORGANIZATION> Mercedes-Benz </ORGANIZATION>. <ORGANIZATION> UNRWA </ORGANIZATION> was notified.'' He gave no other details. No comment was available immediately from the <ORGANIZATION> U.N. </ORGANIZATION> agency, which cares for Palestinian refugees in the <LOCATION> Middle </LOCATION> <LOCATION> East </LOCATION>. Black flags and posters of <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> decorated Shiite Moslem districts of <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and its southern slums. The 86-year-old Iranian patriarch died on Saturday of a heart attack in <LOCATION> Tehran </LOCATION> after surgery for internal bleeding. Lebanese cranked up generators to watch <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s funeral broadcast live by the <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, run by right-wing <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> militias. Three months of Syrian-Christian clashes have caused chronic power shortages. Shiite mosques blared verses from the Koran, <ORGANIZATION> Islam </ORGANIZATION>'s holy book, as thousands of mourners flooded the Iranian Embassy to deliver condolences. Cars mounted with loudspeakers drove the streets urging businesses to close. `` Close! Close!'' shouted a bearded man from a car that flew the Iranian flag and blared verses from the Koran as he drove across west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hamra </LOCATION> commercial thoroughfare. `` Sure, sure,'' muttered a grocer, lowering his shutter. Banks and other private businesses that opened after observing a one-day closure also shut down again. Meanwhile, police said the overnight casualties raised the toll in the latest round of fighting in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s 14-year-old civil war to 363 people killed and 1,430 wounded. The battles began on March 8 over a blockade Christian Gen. <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> <PERSON> Aoun </PERSON> imposed on illegal ports run by Syrian-backed Moslem militias. A Arab League committee met for seven hours on Monday and made yet another appeal for a cease-fire. <PERSON> King </PERSON> <PERSON> Hassan </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Morocco </LOCATION>, King Fahd of <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> and President <PERSON> Chadli </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendjedid </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Algeria </LOCATION> make up the committee. The league plans to dispatch a representative to <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> on Thursday to pursue a cease-fire, said reports in <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s leftist newspaper As-Safir and the independent daily An-Nahar.
</TEXT>
