<SECOND>PM-Cosmetic Surgery-Inmates,0332</SECOND>
<HEAD>Medical Branch to Halt Cosmetic Surgery for Prison Inmates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GALVESTON, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> medical school says it will put stricter limits on plastic surgery on inmates, two years after the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> banned frivolous cosmetic surgery at taxpayer expense. `` It is our intent to ` limit down' so that we can stay out of trouble with everybody,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Alvin </PERSON> <PERSON> L. </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON>, vice president for hospital affairs. `` We are going to try to please the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>, I can tell you that.'' A rider to prison appropriations bills passed in 1987 and this year prohibits use of state money for cosmetic surgery on prisoners unless they are disfigured and suffer psychological problems because of it. The university, a state school, operates a 120-bed prison hospital in <LOCATION> Galveston </LOCATION>. The <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> reported two months ago that hundreds of prisoners over the years have gotten facelifts, liposuction _ fat removal _ and other cosmetic surgery. The article quoted a 59-year-old inmate who received face and brow lifts and liposuction as saying, `` I think it will help my attitude and feeling about myself when I go back to the free world.'' School officials were quoted as saying that the practice helps surgeons perfect their skills and improves prisoners' outlook. A prison policy that took effect April 28 requires that requests for cosmetic surgery be approved by the deputy director for medical services in the prison system and a university doctor, officials said. In the past, prison psychiatrists could recommend the surgery. <PERSON> LeBlanc </PERSON> said he was unaware of the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION>'s limit on cosmetic surgery until contacted by the <ORGANIZATION> Houston </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chronicle </ORGANIZATION> on Monday. <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Lynaugh </PERSON>, executive director of the <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corrections </ORGANIZATION>, said, `` We definitely were aware of that rider and have not violated it.'' `` When my inmates check into that hospital, I have no control of anything except security. I do n't control any medical practices in that hospital,'' <PERSON> Lynaugh </PERSON> said.
</TEXT>
