<HEAD>South Bronx Commune Members Share Life of Drugs and Crime</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhotos NY300,301,302,303,304,305 May 31</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP LaserPhoto Package</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK LENNIHAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Staff Photographer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The five men and one woman have shared the boarded-up <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> brownstone since 1983, their lives devoted to drugs and crime. `` We're closer to each other than to our families,'' says <PERSON> Donna </PERSON>, a crack addict who is undergoing methadone treatment to help fight heroin addiction. `` We survive because we take care of each other.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>, 33, is the group leader. Hooked on heroin when he was 11, the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> native has been in and out of methadone programs since he was 18. The methadone blocks his appetite for heroin, but smoking crack, a concentrated cocaine crystal, now satisfies his cravings for a high. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON>, <PERSON> Michael </PERSON> and <PERSON> Fred </PERSON> are crack addicts, too. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> has a heroin habit. The commune members have been evicted four times from the building, which <PERSON> Michael </PERSON>'s parents owned until the city seized it for back taxes. The roof leaks and the ceilings are falling in. The dank hallway reeks of urine. A rotting staircase leads to the second-floor living area. A single bulb illuminates a semicircle of mattresses that are beds by night and sofas by day. Old clothing is stuffed in plastic bags or piled in corners. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>'s pit bull, Coco, is kept chained to a radiator, a deterrent to unwanted visitors. There is no heat or running water. The group members take sponge baths using buckets filled with water taken from a hydrant outside. A plastic pail is their toilet; it is emptied each morning into a sewer pipe out on the street. Each member is responsible for raising the $ 1,000 a week it takes to keep the group's drug habit satisfied. They're willing to talk about their lives and crimes, they say, because they have nothing to lose. <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> breaks into subway turnstiles and steals tokens. Each token is worth $ 1 to a subway rider; newsstand operators and convenience store owners in the <LOCATION> Bronx </LOCATION> pay him $ 75 for 100 tokens. `` It's a victimless crime. -LRB- We're -RRB- not hurting anybody. -LRB- We're -RRB- taking back a little of what -LRB- we -RRB- gave the city,'' he says. But his crimes are n't always victimless. `` When we ran out of money we've looked at each other and said, ` Let's go hold up a taxi cab driver.' And we did.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> also deals crack. He pays $ 5 for a vial that holds less than a quarter-teaspoon and sells it for $ 10. Some of his regular customers include a <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Island </LOCATION> gas station owner, a stockbroker, a <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> free-lance artist, a former <ORGANIZATION> Amtrak </ORGANIZATION> motorman and a <ORGANIZATION> Xerox </ORGANIZATION> customer service representative. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> steals copper wire from <ORGANIZATION> Metro </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> North </ORGANIZATION> commuter railroad yards and sells it as scrap. He also strips copper wiring and pipes from abandoned refrigerators and buildings, collects abandoned mattresses and recycles bundles of unsold newspapers. <PERSON> Kenny </PERSON> describes himself as a `` real, real, real good thief.'' He shoplifts, specializing in videotapes, electronic goods, medicines and cigarettes. `` I take anything that ai n't nailed down.'' <PERSON> Donna </PERSON>'s monthly welfare check goes for crack. `` The day her welfare check comes in we lay in bed all day getting high,'' says <PERSON> Frank </PERSON>. The group is not unaware of their condition. `` We're living like animals,'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> says. Since their most recent eviction, in February, <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> has picked out two abandoned buildings in the neighborhood in better condition that they can move into. In addition, <PERSON> Donna </PERSON> expects to begin receiving her late husband's Social Security benefits He was a heroin addict who died in December. Their 15-year-old son is in her parents' custody. She and <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> have been thinking of using the benefits to rent an apartment to escape their squalid lifestyle. <PERSON> Albert </PERSON> is convinced he can break his crack addiction and re-enter the mainstream. He has moved into a shelter for homeless men and says, `` I'll be better in a few months, looking for a job.'' <PERSON> Frank </PERSON> is n't so hopeful for himself and the others. `` Some of us are beyond being saved. All of us somewhere in the back of our mind have a death wish. We just do n't have the courage to do it outright.''
