<HEAD>Ex-KKK Leader Stirs Things Up But Changes Little</HEAD>
<HEAD>LaserPhoto upcoming</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA ASHTON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, <PERSON> ex-Ku </PERSON> <PERSON> Klux </PERSON> <PERSON> Klan </PERSON> leader turned ambitious freshman legislator, riled some people with his election, but during his first regular lawmaking session he has hardly made a dent in <LOCATION> Louisiana </LOCATION> government. With the 1989 general session nearing its end, none of his bills has made it through the legislative process. Only one was passed by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and it is pending in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee. `` Some of my legislation's gone through. I mean I'm only a two-month freshman legislator and I think I've done quite well,'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said. It's not unusual for a newcomer to have difficulty getting legislation passed. Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> had a similar experience last year. `` The major difference is <PERSON> David </PERSON> is sort of a one-issue type of guy. He's interested in the racial issue,'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said. The legislative session could end as early as this weekend. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>, 38, was elected in February to represent a nearly all-white district in suburban <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Orleans </LOCATION> after a `` no-tax'' campaign that focused on `` civil rights'' for everyone _ including whites. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> is a former grand wizard of the <ORGANIZATION> Ku </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klux </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Klan </ORGANIZATION>, which he left in 1980 in a dispute with a rival faction. He then formed the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> the </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Advancement </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION>, which he still heads. He ran for president in 1988, first as a Democrat and then on the <ORGANIZATION> Populist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> ticket. He registered as a Republican days before entering the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> race, which he won by 227 votes in a runoff with a long-time Republican who was endorsed by President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> and former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lee </PERSON> <PERSON> Atwater </PERSON> called for <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION>'s censure as a charlatan after the election. A challenge to his seating in the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> fizzled when 69 of 102 lawmakers backed him. Several representatives said they were inundated with calls from constituents across the state insisting that <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> be seated. When the regular session began in April, <ORGANIZATION> Duke </ORGANIZATION> offered nine bills which would, among other things, have eliminated affirmative action and minority set asides and required drug testing for housing project residents and welfare recipients. One Duke bill is dead on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. One is pending in a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee. A third was gutted in committee and sent to the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor, where it was shelved. Six languish in House committees and are not expected to get out. Seated at one end of the back row of desks, <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> is not one of the plentiful lower chamber gadflies. He rarely goes to the microphone to speak on others' bills. <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s legislation seems to be a target for procedural torpedoes, including one fired by Rep. <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Landrieu </PERSON>, a young white legislator whose district includes a housing project. <PERSON> Landrieu </PERSON> got the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> to table <PERSON> Duke </PERSON>'s bill to scrap affirmative action laws. `` It was a short <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and they just happened to get two switch votes which made a difference on that particular vote,'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said. `` What <PERSON> Mitch </PERSON> <PERSON> Landrieu </PERSON> did is he robbed the people of the right to hear the points of view and really have equal rights on this matter. We must have equal rights in this state for everybody.'' Another Duke bill, to deny welfare benefits to drug users by requiring them to be tested, was weakened in a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee to affect only welfare recipients convicted of drug crimes. It is awaiting debate by the full House. The bill in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> committee would require teen-agers to pass drug tests to get driver's licenses, but it was gutted by amendments offered by a black legislator, Rep. C.D. <PERSON> Jones </PERSON>. `` It's a unique situation. He's sort of an internationally known fellow and that puts added pressure on him ... to get a lot accomplished,'' <PERSON> St. </PERSON> <PERSON> Raymond </PERSON> said. `` I told him he could work within the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Caucus </ORGANIZATION> _ ` We'll give you a chance or you can go off and set your agenda.' He's kind of gone off on his own.'' But <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said he believes his presence has made a difference. `` I think I've pushed the whole House of Representatives more to the issues of the middle class and more to the issues of my agenda, my campaign agenda, which is equal rights for all and reform of the welfare system,'' <PERSON> Duke </PERSON> said. `` I think we're moving along quite well.''
