<HEAD>Solidarity Rejects Government's Offer Of Governing Coalition</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 11 grafs to move up to 4th graf reference to prime
minister, Cabinet resignations, EDITS to conform; Pickup 11th graf pvs:
`At a...'</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity said today that despite its overwhelming victory in parliamentary elections it will not accept the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>'s offer to join a governing coalition. In a conciliatory move, however, the free trade union movement offered to stand by the agreement made with authorities in April and allow the party the two-thirds majority in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION>'s powerful lower house Up to 35 of those seats may be vacant because high party and government officials such as Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> appeared to have been defeated in Sunday's vote despite running unopposed. <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> will offer his resignation and that of his Cabinet when the new parliament convenes in June, said deputy government spokesman <PERSON> Zbyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON>. Voters disgruntled by the Communists' more than 40 years of authoritarian rule and mismanagement of the economy gave few of the high-ranking officials the majority needed to gain seats. Solidarity won an overwhelming majority of seats to the new 100-member <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and virtually all the 161 seats it was permitted in the lower house, or <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, according to unofficial returns. A handful of seats may be decided in runoffs on June 18. On Monday, the party conceded defeat in what was <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s most democratic balloting in more than four decades, but fears were raised that the outcome could precipitate a new political crisis. The result gave an opposition group in <LOCATION> Eastern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> control of a freely chosen chamber of <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> for the first time since the postwar Communist takeover. The Communists have urged Solidarity to join a governing coalition, an arrangement unprecedented in the Soviet bloc. `` We can not do reforms by ourselves. ... We need each other,'' <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON> said today. He declined to be specific, saying such questions would have to wait until the new parliament is seated. At a news conference today, Solidarity spokesman <PERSON> Janusz </PERSON> <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> said the union considers itself bound by the April accords in which it agreed to give the government a majority in the 460-member <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> _ 299 seats. Authorities should thus be allowed to fill the vacant seats as they please, he said. <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> ruled out a formal governing coalition: `` All candidates for deputy and senator stated that they will enter the Sejm or <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> as the opposition. That was made very clear.'' But he said that did not rule out future `` joint actions and joint decisions'' to solve specific problems. Senior Solidarity adviser <PERSON> Bronislaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Geremek </PERSON> told reporters the union was ready to act jointly with the government to work for reform. <PERSON> Onyszkiewicz </PERSON> praised Monday's statement by <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jan </PERSON> <PERSON> Bisztyga </PERSON>, who acknowledged the party's electoral defeat. `` It was a very important statement because it shows that the government and the party are committed to a peaceful transition from the present political situation to a more democratic situation,'' he said. Solidarity wants totally free elections in four years, without any pre-reserved seats for either side. Jubilant union supporters celebrated their election win with Russian champagne into the night Monday at <LOCATION> Warsaw </LOCATION> campaign headquarters. Although final official results were not expected until midweek, voters rejected government-backed candidates nearly everywhere. <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s leader, Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON>, on Friday suggested a post-election `` grand coalition,'' though no specific explanations have been given of what he intended. Solidarity's victory was shocking in its proportions for the authorities. Leading officials likely failing to win the necessary votes for a seat in <ORGANIZATION> Parliament </ORGANIZATION> include Interior Minister <PERSON> Czeslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Kiszczak </PERSON> and eight of the ruling Politburo's 17 members, including No. 2 <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Czyrek </PERSON>. Though rejected, the government officials are allowed to keep their posts. In his dramatic concession of defeat Monday, <PERSON> Bisztyga </PERSON> acknowledged on television a `` decided majority'' for Solidarity and appealed for calm. With or without a formal coalition of Solidarity and the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> leadership that long sought to crush it, it appeared certain the two would have to cooperate. The government needs Solidarity if it is to end a protracted economic crisis that includes 80 percent inflation that last year touched off a series of crippling strikes. The country has a $ 39 billion foreign debt. The Solidarity-controlled <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> will have veto power over all legislation, and could only be overridden by a two-thirds majority in the Sejm. But with at best a 65 percent majority of the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> seats, the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> and its allies would need at least 10 Solidarity votes in the lower house to override a veto. The Sejm and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are required to convene after June 18 to elect the president, a new office the Communists had hoped to award to <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> through a majority in the Sejm.
