<HEAD>Gallery Owner Says Dealer Was Diligent in Researching Mosaics</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: LEADS with 12 grafs to UPDATE with New York dealer saying Indianapolis
was diligent in seeking information on the mosaics. PICKS UP 8th graf pvs,
`Goldberg testified ...'; DELETES last two grafs to tighten.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JODI PERRAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>INDIANAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> art dealer testified today that <PERSON> Peg </PERSON> <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> `` left no stone unturned'' in her attempt last summer to learn whether four sixth-century Christian mosaics offered for sale were stolen. `` I think her inquiry met the best professional standards,'' said <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON>, owner of <PERSON> Andre </PERSON> <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON> <PERSON> Gallery </PERSON>. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>'s ownership of the mosaics is being challenged by the Republic of <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and its <ORGANIZATION> Greek </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Orthodox </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION>, who claim the works were stolen from a church in northern <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION> and smuggled out of the <LOCATION> Mediterranean </LOCATION> island nation. They are asking a federal judge to order the suburban <LOCATION> Indianapolis </LOCATION> dealer to return the mosaics. On Monday, <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> testified she believed the man who sold her the four mosaics obtained them legally. She also said she made inquiries around the world to see if any claims had been made against the art. <PERSON> Emmerich </PERSON>, a witness for <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON>, said in a videotaped deposition that comparing her with international dealers would be like comparing `` the corner store to <ORGANIZATION> Bloomingdale </ORGANIZATION>'s.'' But he said her investigation of the mosaics before she purchased them was as complete as any more-experienced dealer would have made. `` I could n't have expected more. She left no stone unturned,'' he said. He said the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, which <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> contacted by telephone, is considered the most complete and readily available source on stolen artwork. The mosaics, which are believed to date to 525 A.D., depict <PERSON> Jesus </PERSON> <PERSON> Christ </PERSON> as an adolescent, the apostles <PERSON> James </PERSON> and <PERSON> Matthew </PERSON> and an archangel. They are among only a handful of icons surviving from the first centuries of Christianity. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> on Monday testified she believed <PERSON> Aydin </PERSON> <PERSON> Dikmen </PERSON>, who sold her the mosaics, had been an archaeologist for the <LOCATION> Turkish </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> of </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Northern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Cyprus </LOCATION>. She said she did not know the breakaway government is not recognized by the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. She said she was told `` that in the process of his other duties, he had found these pieces, that he had been able to make application to acquire them and that had subsequently been granted by the government.'' <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> testified she called customs officials in the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Turkey </LOCATION> and found no claims against the mosaics. She said she also called <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Switzerland </LOCATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Foundation </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Art </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Research </ORGANIZATION>, which keeps an inventory of stolen art. She did not ask <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> if the mosaics were stolen, only whether any treaties would prevent her from bringing them to the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, and was told no, she testified. <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said she asked the art foundation whether it had any record of the mosaics being reported stolen and was told no. <ORGANIZATION> UNESCO </ORGANIZATION> and several other international art groups did have reports that the mosaics were stolen. On cross-examination by attorney <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> R. </PERSON> <PERSON> Kline </PERSON>, <PERSON> Goldberg </PERSON> said she could not recall the names of the people she talked to.
