<HEAD>Americans Gave $104 Million to Charity in '88</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: For release 6:30 p.m. EDT</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans gave $ 104 billion to charity last year, almost 7 percent more than 1987 and 1.8 percent ahead of the inflation rate, according to a report Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Fund-Raising </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Counsel </ORGANIZATION>. The association, which represents fund-raising counseling firms, said the total was up $ 6.55 billion over 1987, breaking the $ 100 billion mark for the first time. Individuals provided about $ 87 billion, foundations $ 6 billion and businesses $ 4.8 billion. Bequests _ gifts willed by the deceased _ amounted to $ 6.8 billion. Religious institutions and causes received the largest share of donations, $ 48 billion, with education, health and human services and cultural organizations getting most of the balance. The association attributed the increase in giving to a 7.5 percent increase in personal income as well as a stronger stock market in the last two months of 1988.
