<SECOND>AM-Foley-In Waiting,800</SECOND>
<HEAD>The New Speaker: Business As Usual in Extraordinary Times</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-House Leadership Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> sat alone over a draft of his resignation speech, while nearby in the Capitol, <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> Majority Leader <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> hosted a breakfast meeting with <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration budget officers. All around him last week, ambitious Democrats were scrambling for support in <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> leadership races, but not <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>. `` I was not going to campaign for an office for which there was no vacancy,'' he would say later. Tuesday, just after noon, the man from <LOCATION> Spokane </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wash. </LOCATION>, filled the vacancy. <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> was out as Speaker of the House. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> was in. Throughout the turmoil over <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s political demise, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> went out of his way to conduct business as usual. Budget meetings, funerals, a ride down Main Street _ he kept to a normal schedule during an extraordinary week. `` It was a very very wrenching time,'' he says now. `` I would have hoped if I had a chance to become speaker, it would have happened through the normal succession.'' His activities during this unusual succession may provide a hint of his leadership style in the House. Publicly, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> worked to keep the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> moving on a legislative agenda that slipped badly over the past several months. Privately, he played a quiet, behind-the-scenes role in the tumultuous events. Some Democrats urged <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>, 60 years old and a 25-year veteran of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION>, to distance himself from the wounded speaker. He refused, telling a reporter, `` I believe strongly in political loyalty.'' `` It has n't been that difficult to stick with <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>,'' he added. In fact, political observers would have been astonished to see <PERSON> Foley </PERS