ay </PERSON> cases, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> said. In private back at the Capitol, trusted by both sides, he played a quiet role in ill-fated negotiations that would have brought <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s immediate resignation in exchange for dismissal of some charges by the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> ethics committee. He had been <PERSON> Wright </PERSON>'s occasional confidant, as well. Twice during recent months, <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> indicated he was thinking of stepping down at the end of his term and told <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> he should prepare to become speaker. Both times, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> urged <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> to avoid any precipitous decisions. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> and <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> met last Tuesday morning, ostensibly to discuss the week's legislative agenda, but the speaker broached the subject of resignation and again made clear he wanted to lay his case before the country and <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> and also wanted a permanent record in the annals of the House. Wednesday began with the budget summit, but within hours <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> told <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> he intended to make a speech on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor _ a signal he was going to resign. A flurry of meetings in <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s office followed, including one with Rep. <PERSON> Julian </PERSON> <PERSON> Dixon </PERSON>, D-Calif., chairman of the ethics committee <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> spent the next several hours on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> floor. In the process, he informed Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of the speaker's decision <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> asked <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> to preside over the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and it was <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> who recognized the speaker for his hour-long resignation speech. Afterward, <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> quickly was on the phone asking colleagues for support, now that he could make an open bid for the speakership. There were no other contenders. But he said he had learned from former Speaker <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> `` Tip'' <PERSON> O'Neill </PERSON> not to take anything or anyone for granted. `` People like to be asked for their support one-on-one,'' he said.
