<HEAD>Boston-Washington Corridor Is Home to One in Six Americans</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The massive Boston-Washington urban corridor is home to one in six Americans, the <ORGANIZATION> Census </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> reported Tuesday. Data from a new census study also show that the corridor contains almost one in four of the Americans who reside in metropolitan areas. The data, for 1987, showed 43.5 million people residing in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Coast </LOCATION> corridor which includes 25 contiguous metropolitan statistical areas. With a national population of 243,396,000 people as of July 1, 1987, that means about 17 percent of the nation lived in the megalopolis. And the bureau reports that 187,072,000 Americans lived in metropolitan areas, nearly 23 percent of them in the <LOCATION> Boston-Washington </LOCATION> region. There are four major clusters within the <LOCATION> Boston-Washington </LOCATION> region: <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York-Philadelphia </LOCATION>, 27.8 million; Boston-Providence, <LOCATION> R.I. </LOCATION>, 6.2 million; <LOCATION> Washington-Baltimore </LOCATION>, 6.1 million and <LOCATION> Harrisburg-York </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Pa. </LOCATION>, 1 million.
