<HEAD>Jackson Urges Bank to Make Loans for Housing and Small Firms</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Jesse </PERSON> <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> asked <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> senators Tuesday to create a domestic world bank which would make loans for housing and small businesses and generate revenue for government services. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON>, a former presidential candidate, spoke at a private meeting of about 20 Democrats on investment plan, which would make heavy use of pension funds but require no tax money. The bank would get its pool of capital from 10 percent of the $ 800 billion in public pension funds and money that private pension programs would be willing to invest, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> told reporters. The program would be administered by a board of labor, management and government representatives. He said the bank would make government-secured loans which could `` begin to build affordable housing, economically integrated housing, small and medium-sized businesses.'' The loans would `` generate revenue, which of course pays taxes for a health plan, and for police and fire services and for education,'' he said. <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said the senators exhibited `` a great degree of optimism'', adding that Sens. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Patrick </PERSON> <PERSON> Moynihan </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, and <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Lieberman </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>., promised to conduct hearings on the idea The investment plan is needed, <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said, because the budget deficit prohibits substantial investment in rural and urban <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, and `` banks and insurance companies, with redlining, would not invest in urban or rural <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.'' `` The Democratic Party ... is at a point to take the offensive, to take the lead,'' <PERSON> Jackson </PERSON> said. `` Right now, the headlines are dominated by the leadership changes on the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> side and focused on personal ethics. There is no focus on the ethical challenge to rebuild <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>.''
