<SECOND>AM-Oil Spill,0469</SECOND>
<HEAD>Leaking Oil Line Exempt From Federal Inspection</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CRAIG, Colo. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Amoco pipeline that spilled crude oil into the <LOCATION> Yampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> last week is among hundreds of miles of <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> pipelines exempted from government safety inspections, officials say. The oil industry persuaded the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration in 1985 to drop all federal maintenance inspections of that type of oil pipeline, known as a gathering line. As a result, the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transportation </ORGANIZATION>'s Office of Pipeline Safety no longer conducts regular checks on the <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> line, which leaked about 10,000 gallons of light crude Friday into the <LOCATION> Yampa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> in northwestern <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>. But an <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> spokesman said the company meets federal standards on such lines. The spill was declared contained Sunday, and much of the oil that was not contained broke up or was washed away in the swiftly flowing river, officials said. But they said there still could be long-range effects on the environment. That part of the river is home to three endangered fish species. Traces of the spill were found as far away as 100 miles downriver from the site. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Overly </PERSON>, who oversees oil-pipeline inspections in 12 Western states from the transportation department's <LOCATION> Denver </LOCATION> regional office, said he did n't have figures on the number of miles of pipeline were exempted from regulation. But he estimated the total as 1,000 miles in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION> alone. `` If this leak was caused by corrosion, we definitely could have had an effect on this pipeline'' if it still were subject to federal regulation and inspection, Overly said. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> executives said the company still does not know what caused the leak. But Overly, noting that the leak occurred where the pipeline passed beneath the river, said rust `` is the first thing I would suspect.'' The 6-inch line carried more than 100,000 gallons of crude oil a day. A gathering line generally links an oil field with storage tanks. The transportation department still inspects about 500 miles of oil pipelines in <LOCATION> Colorado </LOCATION>, Overly said. Those pipelines are called transmission lines, and they generally link refineries with major distribution points. <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Rigg </PERSON> confirmed that the 106-mile pipeline involved in the leak, linking an oil field near <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> with storage tanks in <LOCATION> Wamsutter </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Wyo. </LOCATION>, is subject to no state or federal inspections. He said <ORGANIZATION> Amoco </ORGANIZATION>'s policy on maintenance is to `` comply with ... federal regulation'' on all company pipelines, even though the regulations no longer apply to gathering lines. He said the line at <PERSON> Craig </PERSON> was inspected in 1985 and repaired in 1986. Overly said that <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> administration officials exempted gathering lines from federal regulation after oil executives said the pipes did n't pose serious threats to public health because most pass through remote terrain.
