<HEAD>Pipeline Servicing City May Reopen Friday</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LAS VEGAS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A pipeline that provided 90 percent of the gasoline for the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> area before it exploded in <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> could be back in operation by Friday, which could mean a drop in prices at the gas pump. Prices jumped as much as a nickel a gallon when the pipeline exploded May 25 in <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Bernardino </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, killing two people and injuring 31. The blast knocked out the <ORGANIZATION> Calnev </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> pipeline that carried gasoline and diesel fuel from <LOCATION> Southern </LOCATION> <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> refineries to the <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Oil companies had to ship gasoline 300 miles by truck, increasing the cost of transportation. <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION>, the dominant oil company in southern <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, raised its prices to dealers 5 cents a gallon in the first days following the explosion. <ORGANIZATION> Arco </ORGANIZATION> officials say the company's prices `` absolutely'' will drop once the line reopens. <ORGANIZATION> Chevron </ORGANIZATION> officials say it cost an extra 6 -LCB- cents a gallon to truck gasoline to <LOCATION> Las </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Vegas </LOCATION>, and not all costs were passed on to dealers. No gasoline shortages or service station lines have been reported in the city. The price for self service unleaded gasoline has been running $ 1.10 to $ 1.12 a gallon since the pipeline explosion.
