<HEAD>Army Major Acquitted of Participating in Coup Plot</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A military court on Tuesday acquitted an army major of charges that he took part in an attempt to overthrow the government of President <PERSON> Corazon </PERSON> <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> in 1987. The five-man military tribunal said the prosecution failed to produce evidence that Maj. <PERSON> Horacio </PERSON> <PERSON> Lactao </PERSON> disregarded lawful orders from a superior officer. <PERSON> Lactao </PERSON> led about 30 soldiers aboard a column of tanks and armored personnel carriers from the army training camp in <LOCATION> Nueva </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Ecija </LOCATION> province to <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION> at the height of the bloodiest of six coup attempts against Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON>. The coup on Aug. 28, 1987, left at least 53 people dead and hundreds others wounded. Military troops loyal to Mrs. <PERSON> Aquino </PERSON> blocked <PERSON> Lactao </PERSON>'s group before it entered <LOCATION> Manila </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Lactao </PERSON> said he did not violate any orders when he led the convoy back to the training camp on his own. Last year, <PERSON> Lactao </PERSON> and his men were cleared by another court martial of charges of mutiny.
