Akhromeyev </PERSON> _ and he and I had many hours together talking _ that it was very fruitful, at least from my perspective,'' <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> said. `` We clarified things. We attempted to brush away some of the misunderstandings. There are a lot of questions that military people always carry around in their minds. Often we develop on our own the wrong answers. This gives me an opportunity to address my counterparts directly,'' he said. `` When Marshal <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON> departed last year, I felt much better about what I knew and what they were saying and so forth,'' said <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>. The admiral said that <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION> intelligence on Soviet military capabilities `` has been good, but obviously in certain areas we have done better than in others. `` We have been surprised on occasion. We have not done as well as we would prefer. Marshal <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON> and I actually talked about that. I think there is a built-in tendency to overestimate the strength of ... opponents,'' he said. `` Marshal <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON> and I on occasion pointed out to each other that he did n't understand our forces ... I told him that he overestimated my capability and he told me that I greatly overestimated his. He was talking about ground and I was talking about <ORGANIZATION> Navy </ORGANIZATION>,'' said <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON>, a naval officer. <PERSON> Akhromeyev </PERSON> is an army officer. <PERSON> Crowe </PERSON> also predicted that the two sides would discuss the military crackdown in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and developments in <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Korea </LOCATION>. `` We will both have some curiosity about the other's feelings about what is going on in that part of the world.
