<HEAD>Florida Governor Sets Special Election Dates For Pepper's Seat</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN SEWELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The race is on for the seat left vacant by the death of Rep. <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON>, with early expectations that the Aug. 29 special election called Tuesday could produce the first Cuban exile in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Gov. <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> announced the election schedule one day after burial of the 88-year-old congressman following a week of ceremonies and mourning. `` <PERSON> Claude </PERSON> <PERSON> Pepper </PERSON> will be difficult, if not impossible, to replace in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. But it's vitally important that we move as quickly as possible so that the people of <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION>'s 18th congressional district can be represented,'' <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said. Some leaders of the <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>, riding a wave of <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> momentum in the state, were focusing upon state Sen. <PERSON> Ileana </PERSON> <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> as their leading candidate for the seat that had been held by Pepper, a liberal Democrat, since its inception. <PERSON> Carlos </PERSON> <PERSON> Perez </PERSON>, a Cuban-born millionaire banana importer and active supporter of <PERSON> Ronald </PERSON> <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> and <PERSON> Oliver </PERSON> <PERSON> North </PERSON>, also said he will run as a Republican. Democrats, with a longer list of interested candidates, had no one publicly committed. `` The Democrats should probably rally behind one candidate,'' said <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Rosario </PERSON> <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, a Cuban-American among the potential Democratic contenders. `` But it's too early.'' A first primary was set for Aug. 1 and any runoff would be Aug. 15. <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> said elections would be held on the same day to replace state officeholders who seek the congressional seat. Under state law, they have to resign before they run. Candidates must file their nominating petitions with the state Division of Elections on June 19 or 20. Pepper, known nationwide for his efforts on behalf on the elderly, won every election for the district since the first in 1962, with his closest race in the past decade a 61-39 percent victory in 1984 over Cuban-American <PERSON> Ricardo </PERSON> <PERSON> Nunez </PERSON> Last year, he had no opposition at all. But Republicans have gained strength in the district, as <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> registration has sagged from 72 percent a decade ago to 54 percent now. Hispanics, estimated by some politicians to comprise nearly half the district, are considered likely to support a <LOCATION> Cuban </LOCATION> candidate. It's estimated that three-quarters of Cuban-American voters in the region are Republican. `` I think the chances are pretty good for a Cuban-American to be elected from that district,'' said <PERSON> Sergio </PERSON> <PERSON> Bendixen </PERSON>, a Democratic strategist. `` Without a doubt, that person would be the most powerful Cuban-American in the country.'' <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Xavier </PERSON> <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, elected in 1985 as the city's first Cuban-born mayor, ruled himself out of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> race Tuesday. <PERSON> Suarez </PERSON>, an independent, did n't formally endorse anyone but praised <PERSON> Ros-Lehtinen </PERSON>. She meanwhile said she would hold a news conference Wednesday to discuss her future. Republican state Rep. <PERSON> Al </PERSON> <PERSON> Gutman </PERSON>, a Cuban-born Jew whose heritage fits two large ethnic groups in the district, was also mulling his possibilities Tuesday. On the Democratic side, state Sen. <PERSON> Jack </PERSON> <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON> said he will decide by Friday whether to run. <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>, 67, shares much of Pepper's constituency and liberalism, but may have problems with Hispanic voters because of his opposition to Nicaraguan Contra aid and other foreign policy issues. <PERSON> Raul </PERSON> <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON>, Cuban-born mayor of <LOCATION> Hialeah </LOCATION>, has long said he'd like to run for <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, but spokesman <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Bovo </PERSON> said <PERSON> Martinez </PERSON> would wait to hear <PERSON> Gordon </PERSON>'s decision Other potential Democratic candidates include Commissioner <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION> Mayor <PERSON> Alex </PERSON> <PERSON> Daoud </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Dade </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> Commissioner <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Gersten </PERSON>, State Attorney <PERSON> Janet </PERSON> <PERSON> Reno </PERSON> and former school board chairman <PERSON> Paul </PERSON> <PERSON> Cejas </PERSON>. Cejas and <PERSON> Kennedy </PERSON> are Cuban-born. In the 1988 elections, <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> gave <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> his largest margin in any state and Republicans gained a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> seat, two House seats and two state Cabinet jobs. Republicans then claimed a 10-9 majority in the congressional delegation when Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Grant </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Tallahassee </LOCATION> switched parties after the election.
