<FIRST>u i AM-AIDS Bjt   06-06 0648</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-AIDS, Bjt,0666</SECOND>
<HEAD>Studies Show AIDS Decoy Drug May Reduce Virus</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DANIEL Q. HANEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Science Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTREAL (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A decoy drug designed to hopelessly confuse the AIDS virus by mimicking its natural target is safe and may lower levels of the lethal virus inside the body, researchers said Tuesday. Scientists said they were encouraged by the results, but they cautioned that testing is at an early stage, and no one can be sure how effective the medicine will be in stopping AIDS. `` Nevertheless, this represents an exciting step forward,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Ian </PERSON> <PERSON> Weller </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Middlesex </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> School </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Medicine </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> England </LOCATION>. The drug is known as soluble CD4, and it is one of more than a dozen currently being used experimentally against the AIDS virus. So far, only one medicine, AZT, has been approved by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> for use against HIV, the AIDS virus. While it can prolong the lives of people with AIDS, it does not cure the disease, and it has a variety of toxic side effects. `` It's clear that we desperately need alternative treatments to AZT,'' said Dr. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> Merigan </PERSON> of <ORGANIZATION> Stanford </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION>. Reports on CD4 and other potential AIDS drugs were presented at the 5th International Conference on AIDS, the major annual meeting to review progress against the epidemic. Dr. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Mason </PERSON>, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> assistant secretary for health, said progress in drug development `` is another success in our war against this terrible infection.'' <PERSON> Mason </PERSON> also it is increasingly important to set up voluntary programs to contact sexual partners of HIV-infected people so they will know of their risk of catching the virus. CD4 is one of a growing group of medicines that are specifically designed to exploit the built-in weaknesses of the AIDS virus. In this case, the medicine is a synthetic copy of a molecule called CD4. These molecules cover the surface of a particular variety of blood cells known as helper T cells. These cells orchestrate the body's immune system, and they are the chief targets of HIV. The virus finds them by zeroing in on CD4. Researchers reason that by flooding the bloodstream with copies of CD4, the virus will mistakenly attack these decoys and miss the blood cells. In preliminary studies on 18 people at the <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Cancer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION>, doctors found that short-term treatment with CD4 appeared to reduce the amount of virus in their bodies by about 50 percent. However, Dr. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarchoan </PERSON>, who directed the study, cautioned that such fluctuations can occur naturally and might not have resulted from the drug. None of the patients got better during the 19-day experiment. `` The results could have been better, but they could have been a lot worse,'' <PERSON> Yarchoan </PERSON> said. `` I still have a lot of enthusiasm for this approach. It has one of the best chances of therapeutic effect with the least toxicity of anything being discussed right now.'' A second preliminary study, conducted on 30 patients at <ORGANIZATION> San </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Francisco </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> England </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Deaconess </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Hospital </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION>, found no clear evidence of viral reduction. The two studies were intended primarily to determine how large a dose of the medicine can be safely given. Dr. <PERSON> J. </PERSON> <PERSON> Davis </PERSON> <PERSON> Allan </PERSON>, who led the study at the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> hospital, said, `` I am very encouraged that the drug appears to be safe. The study was not designed to detect subtle degrees of efficacy. We may have not reached the effective dose yet.'' Researchers hope to make CD4 last longer in the bloodstream by chemically welding it to part of an antibody. They also have developed another hybrid that joins CD4 with a poison, a combination that might kill infected cells that make virus inside the body. <PERSON> Merigan </PERSON> said that 17 experimental AIDS drugs are being given to 7,000 patients in studies sponsored by the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutes </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION>, and tests of six more will start soon.
</TEXT>
