<HEAD>Alameda County Enacts Emergency Assault Weapon Sales Ban</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An ordinance immediately banning the sale of military-style assault weapons in unincorporated areas of <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> was passed Tuesday by the county Board of Supervisors. The 5-1 vote followed action by Gov. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Deukmejian </PERSON> and the Legislature restricting the sale of more than 50 kinds of semiautomatic assault weapons throughout <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>. Supervisor <PERSON> Don </PERSON> <PERSON> Perata </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> Alameda </LOCATION> <LOCATION> County </LOCATION> ordinance closes a loophole in the state measure, which allows people to buy semiautomatic weapons until January and to apply for permits to keep them after January. The state law created a `` window of opportunity'' to buy the weapons, <PERSON> Perata </PERSON> said. `` This ordinance intends to ban such sales immediately in the county to prevent those who would evade the law from stockpiling an arsenal while these weapons are still legally available,'' he said. He said he was concerned about weapon stockpiling by drug dealers and others who have `` ravaged our communities.''
