were traveling in opposite directions and had made unscheduled stops in the valley in the <LOCATION> Ural </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mountains </LOCATION>. Soviet President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> and other officials have charged that workers in charge of the pipeline noticed a drop in pressure before the blast, but increased pressure instead of shutting the line down. `` Vremya'' said Tuesday night that the workers continued to pump gas through the pipeline for 55 minutes after the blast. An exasperated <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, briefing parliamentarians Monday after he returned from the scene, cited `` incompetence, irresponsibility, mismanagement, disgrace'' in the work of the pipeline. <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON>, also speaking to <ORGANIZATION> Izvestia </ORGANIZATION>, said the secret police had sent a team of investigators to the area near <LOCATION> Ufa </LOCATION> to establish the truth. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> was carrying out a `` careful investigation of the reasons and circumstances of this extraordinary event. We understand the great difficultly of this work.'' The <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> `` will do all that's possible to establish the truth and publicize the results of our work,'' he said. <PERSON> Kryuchkov </PERSON> said the <ORGANIZATION> KGB </ORGANIZATION> was working with prosecutors and the Interior and Health ministries. The blast was heard 16 miles away, and the Soviet military chief of staff, Gen. <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Moiseyev </PERSON>, told the official <ORGANIZATION> Tass </ORGANIZATION> news agency Monday that it had the power of 10,000 tons of <ORGANIZATION> TNT </ORGANIZATION>, or half the power of the first atomic bomb that was dropped on <LOCATION> Hiroshima </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Japan </LOCATION>. Many of the vict