<SECOND>AM-Poland-Future,0833</SECOND>
<HEAD>After Elections, Who Will Govern Poland?</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN DANISZEWSKI</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WARSAW, Poland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Solidarity says it does not want to govern despite its overwhelming public mandate in Sunday's parliamentary elections. But if the independent union wo n't, who will? That's the question facing both the opposition and government authorities following Solidarity's big victory over the communist party in the first largely democratic elections in the <LOCATION> East </LOCATION> bloc in more than four decades. The communist <ORGANIZATION> Polish </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Workers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> is making no secret of the fact that it wants some sort of coalition or alliance with the Solidarity-led opposition. As deputy government spokesman <PERSON> Zbyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> Rykowski </PERSON> said Tuesday, `` We need one another.'' But Solidarity was born and thrived as an opposition movement and has no appetite for assuming power in any way but through completely unfettered elections in four years. Solidarity-endorsed candidates accumulated majorities of 70-80 percent Sunday in practically every race they entered. Out of 261 candidates for the two-chamber national legislature, it seems that only eight failed to get the 50 percent of the vote needed to avoid a runoff election on June 18. In a normal parliamentary democracy, Solidarity next would peacefully assume the reins of power. But the Polish elections were governed by the inescapable reality that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> remains a communist state. And so, before agreeing to the elections, authorities were able to insist on reserving 65 percent of the parliament seats only for communists and their allies. As it turned out, the communists were having trouble filling even these `` guaranteed'' seats. Some of the party's best-known leaders, including Prime Minister <PERSON> Mieczyslaw </PERSON> <PERSON> F. </PERSON> <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> and eight Politburo members, appear to have been rejected by more than half the voters even though they ran unopposed for parliament on a `` national list'' of 35 candidates. In a magnanimous gesture, the Solidarity leadership affirmed Tuesday that it will live up to the 65 percent-35 percent division of the parliament's lower house, the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION>, that was provided for under the April 3 accord between the union and government on sweeping social reforms. But while that saves the party from having to stage a messy court or parliament fight for its seats, it does not allay the humiliation of the party's loss and the resulting undermining of its standing at home and abroad. Everyone now understands that in fully free elections, the party would not stand the slightest chance of winning office. Anticipating the loss of the `` national list'' in an informal talk with reporters last week, senior Politburo member <PERSON> Jozef </PERSON> <PERSON> Czyrek </PERSON> was blunt about the possibilities. Defeat of the list `` would be the biggest political joke ever committed in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>,'' he said, with Polish reform communists who agreed to the elections being perceived as having committed political suicide. `` They would be laughing like mad in <LOCATION> Prague </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Berlin </LOCATION>,'' two hardline communist capitals, he added. With its lack of support evident, the party is looking to bolster itself by drawing Solidarity into a `` grand coalition.'' Solidarity insists it wants to remain in opposition, but the political weakness of the party makes that seem more and more difficult. Because of its numbers in the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> and its mass popular support, the independent union will have a huge say in policy and appointments. For instance, no legislation will be able to get through the new <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Assembly </ORGANIZATION> without Solidarity votes. The <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> has a veto over all bills, and the party lacks enough votes in the Sjm to override the veto. There is also the question of naming a new president and forming a new government after the new <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are seated. Theoretically, <PERSON> Rakowski </PERSON> could keep his post despite having been denied a parliament seat. But it might be difficult for him to function effectively as prime minister after such a loss of face, and there likely will be calls for someone more popular with the voters to head the government. Similarly, the <ORGANIZATION> Sejm </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> are to meet together to name a president, a newly created executive office with strong powers under <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION>'s revamped constitution that was designed to be a bulwark to keep <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in the Soviet bloc. The presidential election was supposed to be a walkaway for Polish party leader Gen. <PERSON> Wojciech </PERSON> <PERSON> Jaruzelski </PERSON> because of the party's built-in majority in the Sejm But if the `` national list'' seats are still vacant when the vote is taken, the party will have only a small three-vote edge. There have been popular calls for Solidarity leader <PERSON> Lech </PERSON> <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON> to offer himself as the opposition's candidate. Such calls are only likely to increase given the Solidarity election performance. President <PERSON> Walesa </PERSON>? Such strange things are starting to look possible now that <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> has started down the road of democracy.
</TEXT>
