<TEXT>
 A 14-year-old girl was raped and strangled in her grandparents' home, where she had moved to get away from the crime and drug abuse in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION>, her teacher said. `` That's what makes this so sad,'' said <PERSON> Jewell </PERSON> <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON>, principal of the school <PERSON> Andrea </PERSON> <PERSON> Nicole </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> had attended. `` She came here to get away from violence and the things that wrap young people up in the city,'' <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said. `` She said many times she wanted to get away from that.'' The girl's body was found Sunday, the same day her grandparents, <PERSON> John </PERSON> and <PERSON> Elmira </PERSON> <PERSON> Hawkins </PERSON>, had left for a weeklong <LOCATION> Florida </LOCATION> vacation. An autopsy showed she had been raped and strangled. An aunt discovered the girl's body. The teen-ager was scheduled to graduate Saturday with the six other members of the eighth grade at the Seventh Day Adventist school. <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said <PERSON> Miss </PERSON> <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON>, who had two older brothers, went to school in <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> until sixth grade, when she asked to be transferred. She returned to <LOCATION> Philadelphia </LOCATION> for seventh grade and then asked to be sent back to <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Pottsgrove </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Township </LOCATION> near <LOCATION> Stowe </LOCATION> to finish eighth grade, <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said. `` I would see her occasionally at church during her seventh-grade year, when she would visit her grandparents up here,'' <PERSON> Elliott </PERSON> said. `` She would tell me that boys bothered her at school, that children skip classes and she said, ` I'm not being challenged,' and she wanted to come back where she knew there was a challenge.'' No arrests have been made, police said.
