<HEAD>Chinese Media Silent on Crisis</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Chinese media all but ceased to function Tuesday with no mention of a deepening crisis in the national leadership or of fighting between military units. The <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> News </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, usually the mouthpiece of government policy, issued no <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> news, restricting itself to a few dozen foreign stories and fixtures such as weather forecasts. Previously, <ORGANIZATION> Xinhua </ORGANIZATION> used its reports to convey the official line on the weeks of student protests. The agency's silence seemed to indicate that neither the conservatives who ordered Saturday's military crackdown nor the liberals who opposed it are in a position to dictate a new line The nationally televised evening news was narrated entirely by off-screen voices with no anchor and even skipped the usual introduction: `` Viewers, this is the news broadcast. These are the main stories.'' Much of the 30-minute newscast was taken up by timeless feature stories from other cities. It also replayed a video from traffic monitors at several intersections in the city showing stone-throwing and other attacks by civilians against troops arriving to enforce martial law. There were no shots of troops firing on civilians. The only substantial news from television or any other official media Tuesday was a statement by <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> spokesman Yuan Mu that nearly 300 people had died and more than 7,000 were injured. State-run television also said 32 people were arrested, most for allegedly attempting to set fire to buses. Yuan was shown sitting at a desk facing several rows of local officials in a small meeting room, the first look inside the government since Saturday. The television later broadcast a news conference by Yuan with <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> journalists, in which he urged them to do their work well even though newspapers have not been distributed since Saturday. His comment implied that some newspapers continued to print editions even though they were not being delivered or sold on the street. <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Central </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Television </ORGANIZATION> did not broadcast its daily English-language newscast on Monday or Tuesday night, and all stations ended their programming early. Telephone calls to television stations went unanswered. Many Chinese reporters had closely followed the weeks of student pro-democracy protests that led to the May 20 declaration of martial law and Saturday military attack. But since Saturday none have been seen on the streets.
