<HEAD>Drastic Tightening of Ceramic Pitcher Standard Planned</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> The </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Food </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Drug </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it planned a 50-fold reduction in the amount of lead permitted to reach beverages from ceramic pitchers because of new evidence that extremely small amounts of lead can hurt children. Lead at concentrations tolerable by adults can limit body growth and intelligence of children and can cause brain damage and behavior problems. Lead in pitchers comes from the glaze commonly used to make ceramics smooth and impervious. Officials are most concerned about acidic liquids like orange juice eating away at the glaze and causing lead to leach. Small cream pitchers would not be subject to the new standard since they are not used for acidic liquids. The <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> is proposing to allow pitchers to be sold only if they leach no more than 0.1 micrograms, or one-tenth of a millionth of a gram, of lead per milliliter of an acidic test solution. Currently, pitchers are allowed to leach up to 5 micrograms of lead per millileter. The proposal also would require that high-lead decorative and commemorative ceramic plates have fired into them a permanent warning that cautions `` Not for Food Use _ May Poison Food,'' or have holes so they ca n't be used for food. The current standard was set by <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> in 1979 based on recommendations of the <ORGANIZATION> World </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Organization </ORGANIZATION>. However, as a result of the recent studies, the federal <ORGANIZATION> Centers </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disease </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> and the WHO have reduced their recommended maximum levels. The proposed regulation was published in the Federal Register last Thursday. After a 60-day comment period, the <ORGANIZATION> FDA </ORGANIZATION> will issue final rules.
