<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two major studies of the airline industry put radically different slants on the impact of airline hub operations on competition and air fares. A study by the <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Accounting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Office </ORGANIZATION> to be released at a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> hearing Wednesday says airlines charge an average of 27 percent more per passenger mile on flights to and from 15 major hub airports than at other airports included in the study. The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION> obtained an advance copy of the study. But a study by the airline industry released Tuesday says average airline fares have decreased since deregulation of the industry in 1978 and fares at 30 hub airports are only 1.5 percent above the industry average. That study says hub fares are a little higher primarily because hubs tend to have more non-stop flights. Both studies are to be discussed on Wednesday at a hearing of the <ORGANIZATION> Commerce </ORGANIZATION>, Science and Trasporation subcommittee on aviation, which is examining the airline practice of feeding many of their flights through a single airport. The study by the <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION>, which is the investigative arm of <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>, concludes the trend that has seen major airlines dominating flights at airports where they set up hub operations has decreased competition. `` Many travelers have less choice among airlines as more markets are being controlled by a single airline,'' the study says. The report says that although the number of destinations served from hub airports studied increased 10 percent between May 1985 and May 1988, most of the increases were by dominant carriers and were offset by large service reductions by other carriers. At 13 of the 15 hubs studied, average air fares per passenger mile were higher for dominant carriers than for other airlines serving the same airports, the report said. `` Hubbing generates important operating efficiencies, but it can also lead to substantial market power for the airlines, which could lead to higher fares and reduced levels of service,'' <ORGANIZATION> GAO </ORGANIZATION> official <PERSON> Kenneth </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Mead </PERSON> said in testimony prepared for the subcommittee hearing. The industry study conducted by the aviation consulting firm of <ORGANIZATION> Simat </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> , </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Helliesen </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Eichner </PERSON> concludes that competition in individual markets has increased despite the greater concentration within the industry and at some airports. The study commissioned by the <ORGANIZATION> Air </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Transport </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, which represents major airlines, concludes there is little, if any, relationship between average fares and airline concentraiton at either hub or non-hub airports. `` The hub and spoke system has evolved into a highly competitive national transportation system which provides enormous benefits to the American public,'' said <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Aaronson </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> ATA </ORGANIZATION> president. The <ORGANIZATION> ATA </ORGANIZATION> study says better service, such as more non-stop flights, account for average fare levels at some hubs that are higher than the industry average. But, in analyzing the study, the association said passengers are not hostage to the higher fares because cheaper options are available, including multi-stop flights or connecting flights. Airline schedules at 25 non-hub airports show they are now served by nearly twice as many airlines as in 1978, when the airline industry was deregulated, the <ORGANIZATION> ATA </ORGANIZATION> study said. The <ORGANIZATION> ATA </ORGANIZATION> study includes charts which show that in 1978 nearly half of all airline passengers traveled in markets where a single carrier had 70 percent or more of the flights, but in 1988, only 20 percent of passengers traveled in markets that were served by only one airline. `` The growth of the number of hubs and the expansion of service at them have had astonishingly beneficial consequences for the typical spoke community,'' the <ORGANIZATION> ATA </ORGANIZATION> said.
</TEXT>
