 Imprisoned black leader <PERSON> Nelson </PERSON> <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> was allowed a visit Tuesday from <PERSON> Govan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON>, the highest-ranking <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> member at liberty in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON>, 78, received unexpected permission for the visit after being turned down several times since his release from prison in November 1987. It is not known what the veteran black nationalists discussed because <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> is barred from being quoted by the press. No other source of information was available. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> spent about 2 -LCB- hours at <PERSON> Victor </PERSON> <PERSON> Verster </PERSON> prison farm in <LOCATION> Paarl </LOCATION>, outside <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, but the exact length of his meeting with <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION>'s most popular leader was not disclosed. The two last met shortly before <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> was freed. They were among eight <ORGANIZATION> African </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> leaders sentenced to life imprisonment in 1964 for plotting to sabotage the government. <PERSON> Farida </PERSON> <PERSON> Omar </PERSON>, an anti-apartheid activist from <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION>, said she was with <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> when he received a telephone call Tuesday morning informing him the visit had been approved. `` He was very thrilled,'' she said. Rumors of <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>'s possible release have been circulating in <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Africa </LOCATION> for more than a decade, and the government gives no firm indication of its plans. However, the decision last year to move him to a suburban-style ranch house on a prison farm revealed the special status he has even as an inmate. <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON>, 70, has refused offers of freedom on condition he renounces the use of violence in the fight to topple the white-led government. There is speculation that <PERSON> Mandela </PERSON> may be released after national elections in September for whites, Indians and people of mixed-race. The 28 million blacks have no vote in national affairs. <PERSON> Mbeki </PERSON> was freed unconditionally because he was ailing, but a month later was placed under harsh restrictions prohibiting him from leaving his hometown of Port <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> without permission. He has been allowed periodic visits to <LOCATION> Cape </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Town </LOCATION> for medical treatment.
