<HEAD>Lebanon's Shiite Factions Pledge Allegiance to Khamenei</HEAD>
<HEAD>With Khomeini Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MOHAMMED SALAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>'s two main Shiite Moslem factions issued statements Tuesday endorsing President <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Iran </LOCATION>, who was chosen as caretaker leader after the death of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>. New shelling began after nightfall in the 3-month-old artillery war between Christian army units and a a Moslem alliance of Syrian troops and Druse militiamen. No casualties were reported. `` We declare obedience to <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> and swear absolute commitment to his teachings and orders,'' said a statement issued by the pro-Iranian <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION>, or Party of God. <ORGANIZATION> Hezbollah </ORGANIZATION> is the umbrella group for militant Shiites believed to be holding some of the 18 foreigners missing in <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. The rival Amal faction, a more moderate group backed by <LOCATION> Syria </LOCATION>, said it `` supports and blesses the <LOCATION> Islamic </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Republic </LOCATION> in its correct selection of the great successor <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ali </PERSON> <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON>.'' <PERSON> Khamenei </PERSON> is only a middle-ranking cleric, but is being called `` ayatollah'' since his choice by the Assembly of Experts established by <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> to handle the succession. Shiites mourned <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON> for a third day with a general strike in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and other Moslem areas of <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION>. <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, 86, died of a heart attack Saturday, 11 days after intestinal surgery. Black flags and photo posters of the bearded, black-turbaned revolutionary patriarch dangled from buildings and mosques in Moslem west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>, the southern slums and <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> towns in south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> Bekaa </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Valley </LOCATION>. Mourners marched to the Iranian Embassy in the seaside <LOCATION> Ouzai </LOCATION> suburb and <ORGANIZATION> Shiite </ORGANIZATION> religious centers in other cities to deliver condolences. `` Death to <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>, the great Satan,'' read a banner carried by about 200 mourners in the southern port of Tyre. A dozen youths in the Bir el-Abed slum beat their chests and shaved their heads as worshippers entered the district's mosque for a memorial service. The <ORGANIZATION> Lebanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Broadcasting </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, run by rightist <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> militias, broadcast <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>'s funeral live. Cars equipped with loudspeakers toured the streets in west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION> and Tyre urging businesses to close, and most complied. `` Close! Close!'' a bearded man shouted from a white Peugeot that drove across west <LOCATION> Beirut </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Hamra </LOCATION> commercial street flying the Iranian flag and blaring verses of the Koran. `` Sure, sure,'' a grocer replied as he lowered his shutter. The car drove away and the grocer murmured: `` Last year it was a strike to mark the Israeli invasion's anniversary. I wonder whether we'll be alive next June 6 to observe a strike for any reason.'' <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION> withdrew most of its army from <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> in June 1985, ending three years of invasion and occupation of the south. With the aid of a surrogate militia, it maintains a `` security zone'' just inside south <LOCATION> Lebanon </LOCATION> that ranges in depth from 6 to 10 miles. Palestinian guerrilla factions marked the anniversary by issuing statements condemning <LOCATION> Israel </LOCATION>. Police said nine people were wounded in overnight artillery exchanges, raising total casualties to 363 killed and 1,430 wounded since the artillery duels began March 8.
