<HEAD>Senators Told Elderly Being Ripped Off by Check-Handlers</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JEFF BARKER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Elderly Americans are being ripped off by representatives appointed to handle their Social Security checks, a <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> panel was told Tuesday, but lawmakers and the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration disagreed on how to reform the system. An <LOCATION> Arkansas </LOCATION> woman and a <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> woman misused <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> payments that they had been entrusted to manage on behalf of elderly beneficiaries, the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Special </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> on Aging was told at a hearing. <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Freeland </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION>, testified that she was told by the government that she needed a representative to handle her disability benefits because she was incapable of managing the money herself. But she said the woman who was appointed kept some of the benefits for herself, and had a history of writing bad checks. She did not identify the woman. A similar story was told by <PERSON> Mary </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> of <PERSON> Marvell </PERSON>, <LOCATION> Ark. </LOCATION>, who said her representative collected her disability benefits, then refused to use the money to buy a telephone, clothes or other necessities that <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> requested. `` She often would not tell me how much money she would have of mine, or what was going on,'' <PERSON> Miller </PERSON> said. About 4.6 million Social Security beneficiaries have mental or physical impairments serious enough that they require a `` payee'' to manage their benefits. The <ORGANIZATION> Social </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Security </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Administration </ORGANIZATION> accepts applications from anyone who wants to be a payee, but gives preference to relatives or to public or private groups with good records in handling elderly affairs. But Sens. <PERSON> David </PERSON> <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON>, D-Ark., and <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON>, R-Pa., said the government has been too lax in overseeing the `` There is some evidence that <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> has not been keeping a close watch on those who apply to be representative payees,'' <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> said. `` Presently, the <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> does not do background checks, nor does the <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> monitor the program to ensure that the beneficiaries actually receive their money.'' <PERSON> Louis </PERSON> <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON>, an <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> deputy commissioner, said the administration recognized there was a problem, and was evaluating steps to remedy it. He said the victims represent a small percentage of often poor, uneducated or handicapped people who are without relatives to care for them. <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> verifies the identities of payee applicants, and asks them whether they have felony convictions. He said he was concerned about a bill introduced by <PERSON> Pryor </PERSON> and <PERSON> Heinz </PERSON> on Tuesday that would require <ORGANIZATION> SSA </ORGANIZATION> to conduct criminal background checks on applicants, while barring most creditors from becoming payees. A ban on creditors would be too stringent and would keep, for example, helpful landlords from becoming payees, <PERSON> Enoff </PERSON> said. Still other possible safeguards in the bill are not yet feasible, he said. `` Ultimately, we plan to automate pertinent data on payee applicants, including past misuse activity and felony convictions, but the extent to which this can be done requires further investigation, analysis and systems development,'' he said.
