<FIRST>r w AM-Bush-D-Day     06-06 0246</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Bush-D-Day,220</SECOND>
<HEAD>President Marks 45th Anniversary of Invasion</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-D-Day</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> on Tuesday marked the 45th anniversary of the <LOCATION> Normandy </LOCATION> invasion and called for redoubled efforts to help spread democracy around the globe. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in a statement on the anniversary of D-Day, linked the current stuggle in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> and the Allied invasion that hastened the liberation of <LOCATION> Europe </LOCATION> in 1945. `` The turmoil and confusion of battle that day belied the calm purposefulness with which freedom confronts tyranny,'' the president said. `` In recent days, the face of the world has again been marked by dramatic occurrences _ winds of change _ that signify the determination with which freedom confounds its adversaries,'' he said. He recalled that on the morning of June 6, 1944, Gen. <PERSON> Dwight </PERSON> <PERSON> D. </PERSON> <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> `` carried in his pocket a draft message declaring the invasion to have been a failure and taking personal responsibility for that failure.'' `` He never needed to use that draft, of course,'' he added. `` As with Gen. <PERSON> Eisenhower </PERSON> then, we can not know with certainty today whether the forces of freedom will prevail soon or in every instance,'' <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> said. `` Yet the ultimate victory of freedom and democracy is inevitable.'' He said last week's successful <ORGANIZATION> NATO </ORGANIZATION> summit, as well as `` the first free elections in <LOCATION> Poland </LOCATION> in more than 50 years and even the momentous, tragic events in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> give us reason to redouble our efforts to continue the spread of freedom and democracy around the globe.''
