<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 A prominent Soviet writer said during parliamentary debate Tuesday on nationalist unrest that soldiers covered up ethnic violence three years ago in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION>. The debate in the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> People </ORGANIZATION><ORGANIZATION> 's </ORGANIZATION> Deputies took place at a time of more ethnic troubles, this time in the Central Asian republic <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>. At least 50 people were reported killed over the weekend. Writer <PERSON> Mukhtar </PERSON> <PERSON> Sakhanov </PERSON> said a letter from intellectuals in <LOCATION> Kazakhstan </LOCATION> charged that soldiers used dogs and shovels to disperse protesters and that the number of deaths has been kept secret. That protest was the first in a long series of ethnic disturbances under President <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s policy of greater openness and social and economic reform. <PERSON> Sakhanov </PERSON> summarized the letter, then turned it over to <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> during Tuesday's session. It said the number of deaths in rioting in the republic's capital, <ORGANIZATION> Alma </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Ata </ORGANIZATION>, was greater than the 32 killed last year during violence last year between ethnic Armenians and Azerbaijanis `` According to incomplete data, about 3,000 people were arrested, hundreds of them were sentenced to long prison terms, thousands were excluded from schools or fired from work,'' said the letter written by seven Kazakh intellectuals. Copies were circulated in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION> by Kazakh activists. The violence in <LOCATION> Sumgait </LOCATION>, the Azerbaijani capital, was caused by a dispute over <LOCATION> Nagorno-Karabakh </LOCATION>, an enclave in <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> whose population is predominantly Armenian. The territory was assigned to <LOCATION> Azerbaijan </LOCATION> in 1923, but <LOCATION> Armenia </LOCATION> wants to annex it. On April 9, troops battled pro-independence demonstrators in <LOCATION> Tbilisi </LOCATION>, the capital of the Georgian republic, and at least 20 demonstrators were killed. The use of shovels and a debilitating gas by soldiers who broke up that protests has caused national outcry. The Baltic republics of <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Latvia </LOCATION> also have been beds of unrest as activists press for more autonomy. Official reports have said that only a couple of people were killed in the Kazakh rioting, which broke out after the republic's <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief <PERSON> Dinmukhamed </PERSON> <PERSON> Kunaev </PERSON>, an ethnic Kazakh, was replaced by Russian <PERSON> Gennady </PERSON> <PERSON> Kolbin </PERSON> The letter demanded a legislative commission be formed to investigate the rioting. Also Tuesday, Russian writer <PERSON> Valentin </PERSON> <PERSON> Rasputin </PERSON> characterized the dominant <LOCATION> Russian </LOCATION> population as a victim rather than master of the vast Soviet bureaucracy. Ethnic minorities blame centralized control on domination by Russians in <LOCATION> Moscow </LOCATION>, but <PERSON> Rasputin </PERSON>, of the Siberian city <LOCATION> Irkutsk </LOCATION>, said the system had `` plundered <LOCATION> Russia </LOCATION> to such an extent that it is just on this side of survival.'' He complained that when Russians begin talking of their own national culture and traditions, they immediately make other ethnic groups wary. Members of the newly formed Soviet of Nationalities, the house of the Supreme Soviet legislature that is assigned to deal with ethnic questions, also met Tuesday and debated the ethnic unrest issue. It named the <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief of <LOCATION> Uzbekistan </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Rafik </PERSON> <PERSON> Nishanov </PERSON>, as their chairman after questioning him about the violence in his republic. Of 252 deputies present, five voted against <PERSON> Nishanov </PERSON> and 11 abstained. <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>, presiding over the chamber, said the tone of some of the debate `` leads to concern,'' but that he was satisfied with it. `` I'm very pleased because of the informal character of discussion,'' he said. He said the house can not duck hard questions. `` This is the people's life and we have to approach it seriously,'' <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> said. The Soviet of Nationalities met after a morning session of the 2,250-member <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>. Lithuanian deputies demanded veto power over selection of the chairman of the Soviet of Nationalities. When the house refused to go along a deputy who did not identify himself raised the possibility of Lithuanian secession. `` This is a constitutional right, and I do not want my native <LOCATION> Lithuania </LOCATION> to be in such a bad union if it goes like this,'' he said. Deputy <PERSON> Vladimir </PERSON> <PERSON> Yarovoi </PERSON> complained to the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> that Estonian officials were discriminating against others. Reform in <LOCATION> Estonia </LOCATION> is `` a one-way street where there is no place for Russians,'' he said.
