<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration officials and lawmakers clashed Tuesday over legislation calling for U.S.-Soviet negotiations to ban the superpowers' production of plutonium, the material used in nuclear weapons. Under questioning from members of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Armed </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> panel on <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> nuclear facilities, administration officials also conceded that the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has the ability to detect work at <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> reactors that manufacture plutonium. `` Do n't we have the technical ability to pick up a large-scale plant in the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>?'' said Rep. <PERSON> Ron </PERSON> <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON>, D-Ore., one of the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> sponsors of the International Plutonium Control Act After calling the question difficult to answer in an open session, <PERSON> Troy </PERSON> <PERSON> E. </PERSON> <PERSON> Wade </PERSON> <PERSON> II </PERSON>, the <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>'s acting assistant secretary of energy for defense programs, said: `` We can determine if the facility is operating or not operating. Period.'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> and Rep. <PERSON> Bill </PERSON> <PERSON> Green </PERSON>, <LOCATION> R-N.Y. </LOCATION>, testified before the panel on behalf of the legislation that seeks to compel the administration to pursue the negotiations by threatening to block operation of some <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> nuclear weapons facilities. Identical bills introduced in the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> and the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> say that six months after enactment, President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> would be prohibited from operating any of the facilities dedicated to production of plutonium for military purposes unless he certified one of the following conditions: _ The Soviet government refuses to negotiate a ban on plutonium and highly enriched uranium _ The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is unable to determine whether the Soviets have halted production, or _ The Soviets continue to get plutonium by operating civilian <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities geared to plutonium operation are either mothballed or closed permanently. In the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Union </LOCATION>, 14 reactors produce enriched uranium and plutonium for the nuclear arsenal although last month <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader <PERSON> Mikhail </PERSON> <PERSON> S. </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> announced that he would shut down by the end of the year three of 14 reactors that produce enriched uranium and plutonium for the <LOCATION> Soviet </LOCATION> nuclear arsenal. `` The many congressional co-sponsors of the International Plutonium Control Act have, in effect, asked the administration to call Secretary <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON>'s hand on the plutonium issue and negotiate a mutual and verifiable end to production,'' <PERSON> Wyden </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Green </PERSON> said that when Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> met with <PERSON> Gorbachev </PERSON> early last month, the <LOCATION> Kremlin </LOCATION> leader expressed a desire to work on a bilateral agreement on controlling production of all `` weapon-grade fissionable materials.'' `` We should call his bluff,'' <PERSON> Green </PERSON> told the committee. But <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> C. </PERSON> <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON>, assistant director of the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Arms </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Disarmament </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION>, argued against the legislation, saying the absence of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> facilities dedicated to plutonium production versus the more than 10 Soviet reactors would force <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> to negotiate from a position of weakness. In addition, `` this legislation would undermine <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> capability to make strategic nuclear materials in support of our nuclear deterrent. Hampering our capability to produce nuclear weapons before we cease to rely on them is dangerous and destabilizing.'' <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> noted that the Soviet nuclear program does not separate military and civilian facilities while the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> does. If the Soviets decided to `` break out'' of the ban, they could `` send <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> inspectors home, and turn their facilities and plutonium stockpile to weapons purposes.'' The administration argument prompted Rep. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Bilbray </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Nev </LOCATION>., to question whether the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> would have to `` build up its capacity so we can break out. <PERSON> Bailey </PERSON> responded the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> must negotiate from strength, saying that was the case on the U.S.-Soviet treaty to eliminate intermediate-range nuclear missiles. This exchange prompted questions from members as to the amount of plutonium the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> has, with Rep. <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Hochbrueckner </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-N.Y. </LOCATION>, saying he believes that `` we are awash in plutonium.'' But <PERSON> Wade </PERSON>, who declined to provide statistics, saying the information is classified, said: `` I do n't feel awash in plutonium myself.''
