<HEAD>Bright and Brief</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JOHNSON CITY, Tenn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> the pig and <PERSON> Bilbo </PERSON> the hobbit have a lot to teach grade-schoolers if only more educators and parents would stop being afraid of fantasy literature, a professor said Tuesday. Reading aloud in the classroom has grown more popular in the last 15 or 20 years, but such books as `` <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>'s Web'' and `` The Hobbit'' remain on the outskirts of structured curricula, Dr. <PERSON> Roberta </PERSON> <PERSON> Herrin </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Herrin </PERSON> teaches fantasy literature at <ORGANIZATION> East </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Tennessee </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> and is helping coordinate a workshop next week for teachers and librarians on the use of often-classic fantasy tales. The importance of self-esteem is explained through the experiences of <PERSON> Wilbur </PERSON> in `` Charlotte's Web,'' Ms. <PERSON> Herrin </PERSON> said. <LOCATION> Charlotte </LOCATION>, a spider, befriends the self-pitying pig and encourages him to stand on his own four feet. <PERSON> Bilbo </PERSON> <PERSON> Baggins </PERSON> in `` The Hobbit'' finds his true identity after he accepts a challenge from the wizard <ORGANIZATION> Gandalf </ORGANIZATION>. Students are more apt to learn the importance of such traits in the framework of fantasy, Ms. <PERSON> Herrin </PERSON> said. `` You start with a narrative, a story, that engages their interest and move from that to the very practical and concrete applications,'' she said. `` That's very different than coming in and saying, ` Today we're going to study geography.'''
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON, D.C. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 After failing to sell his <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Md. </LOCATION>, home for several months, former Sen. <PERSON> Birch </PERSON> <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>, D-Ind., is taking a different approach The home was listed in a classified ad in Sunday's <ORGANIZATION> Washington </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Post </ORGANIZATION> this way: `` Senator and Mrs. <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> have slashed the price of their <LOCATION> Potomac </LOCATION> home to way below market. They have n't been so beaten down since <PERSON> Dan </PERSON> <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON> did it to'em in 1980.'' <PERSON> Quayle </PERSON>, now vice president, ended <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON>'s <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> career during the <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> landslide of 1980. <PERSON> Bayh </PERSON> and his wife, <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON>, are selling their suburban home to move back into <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION>, he said. `` We decided we would try this to get people's attention.''
