<BYLINE>By LES BLUMENTHAL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Random observations from the day <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> became speaker of the House of Representatives: A CALL FROM REAGAN: The first telephone call <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> received upon returning to his office just moments after being sworn in was from former President <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON>. <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> took the call in private, but said later <PERSON> Reagan </PERSON> called to `` send his best wishes. It was a very generous and kind thing to do.''
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 THE LOYAL OPPOSITION: The three <ORGANIZATION> Republican </ORGANIZATION> members of the <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state congressional delegation have all expressed their admiration for <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> any number of times, but when it came time to vote for him they followed the party line and voted for Republican Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Michel </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Illinois </LOCATION>. However, Reps. <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Miller </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rod </PERSON> <PERSON> Chandler </PERSON> and <PERSON> Sid </PERSON> <PERSON> Morrison </PERSON> joined with the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> members of the delegation to escort <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> to the speaker's rostrum after the vote.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 A PUBLIC MOMENT FOR A PRIVATE LADY: <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s wife, <PERSON> Heather </PERSON>, has always avoided the public spotlight, but when <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> introduced her during his speech the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> gave her a standing ovation. Sitting with her in the gallery were author <PERSON> Kitty </PERSON> <PERSON> Kelley </PERSON>, a longtime friend, and <PERSON> Pamela </PERSON> <PERSON> Harriman </PERSON>, the grand dame of the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 FOR THE RECORD: <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> voted present when his name was called during the voting for speaker. The only other `` present'' vote was cast by <PERSON> Michel </PERSON>.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 FINALLY A SMILE: <PERSON> Foley </PERSON> would have preferred becoming speaker under different circumstances and as he left his office for the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> caucus he said he felt `` more a sense of somber responsibility than excitement.'' As he sat on floor while the roll was called, he had a serious look on his face. He finally broke into a smile when <PERSON> Jim </PERSON> <PERSON> Wright </PERSON> handed him the gavel after the election.
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
 APPLAUSE FROM BEHIND CLOSED DOORS: Rep. <PERSON> Norm </PERSON> <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, D-Wash., said the loudest applause during the <ORGANIZATION> Democratic </ORGANIZATION> caucus came during <LOCATION> California </LOCATION> Rep. <PERSON> Tony </PERSON> <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON>'s seconding speech of <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>'s According to <PERSON> Dicks </PERSON>, <PERSON> Coelho </PERSON> said `` They -LRB- the Republicans -RRB- are the party of <PERSON> Newt </PERSON> <PERSON> Gringrich </PERSON>. We are the party of <PERSON> Tom </PERSON> <PERSON> Foley </PERSON>.''
