<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Here, at a glance, are developments in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> Tuesday:
</TEXT>
<NOTE>ARMIES EXCHANGE FIRE</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Armies loyal to hard-line and moderate government leaders traded gunfire in the capital, winesses said. Witnesses said the 27th Army, which invaded the city Saturday to crush the pro-democracy movement, fought with soldiers from the 28th Army, believed loyal to <PERSON> Zhao </PERSON> <PERSON> Ziyang </PERSON>, the moderate <ORGANIZATION> Communist </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Party </ORGANIZATION> chief who was stripped of his post last month. There were no reports of casualties. Hundreds of citizens flocked to welcome soldiers who said they were from the 38th <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION>, based in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. The 38th Army is said to have opposed the martial law crackdown and refused to fire on civilians.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>U.S. SAYS LEADERS APPARENTLY LEFT CAPITAL</NOTE>
<TEXT>
