</TEXT>
<NOTE>GOVERNMENT STATEMENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 In the first appearance of a top official since last weekend, government spokesman <PERSON> Yuan </PERSON> <PERSON> Mu </PERSON> said <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is `` not afraid'' of the universal condemnation of the government's actions. `` The rebellion has not been completely quelled,'' he said. `` The situation in the capital remains very grim.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OFFICIAL CASUALTIES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 The government announced that nearly 300 people were killed, more than 7,000 were injured and said the figure included soldiers, `` thugs,'' bystanders and 23 students. The official figures were far lower than some unofficial estimates from diplomats of more than 3,000 deaths.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>VIOLENCE CONTINUES</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Soldiers continued firing into crowds around <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>. Witnesses reported a small boy killed and a girl wounded in the head. Police in riot gear cruised the streets in vans as night fell, beating up and shooting passers-by.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>OTHER DEMONSTRATIONS</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Anti-government demonstrations spread to <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nanjing </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Shenyang </LOCATION> and other cities.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>CHINESE DISSIDENT</NOTE>
<TEXT>
 Noted Chinese dissident <PERSON> Fang </PERSON> <PERSON> Lizhi </PERSON> was permitted to take refuge in the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Embassy </ORGANIZATION> in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, a <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> official said.
