<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The Contras on Tuesday again defied <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> pressure to return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> and vote in February's elections, saying they will organize exiles and maintain their military strength. `` The <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> has urged us to return as quickly as possible,'' said <PERSON> Aristides </PERSON> <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON>, spokesman for the Contra directorate's majority. `` But that is counterproductive ... it would be premature.'' Only one of the Nicaraguan rebels' seven directors, <PERSON> Alfredo </PERSON> <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON>, has said he will go back to his homeland without conditions. He is scheduled to arrive in <LOCATION> Managua </LOCATION> next week to begin preparations for national elections. The directorate is based in <LOCATION> Miami </LOCATION>, which was chosen for its proximity to the Central American country and its large Nicaraguan community. <PERSON> Cesar </PERSON>'s action `` shows different criteria, and those are not the criteria of the majority _ we think it divides the opposition,'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. The rebels, who are receiving only non-lethal aid from the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>, will also resist pressure to disband their troops concentrated in Honduran camps just north of the Nicaraguan border, the spokesman said. `` If the elections are a fraud, and if they do not produce a constitutional, free, democratic country, the troops should be viable to take up the struggle again,'' he said. The Contra rebel groups were supposed to be reintegrated into civilian life under the <LOCATION> Central </LOCATION> <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> peace plan approved by the region's presidents, but the <LOCATION> Contra </LOCATION> leadership has refused, accusing the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> of violating their guarantees under the pact. The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration has threatened to renew military aid to the Contras if the national elections are unfair. In an official statement announcing their electoral strategy, the Contra directors pledged Tuesday to deliver a minimum 250,000 Nicaraguan exile votes to the opposition in February. <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>'s population of about 3 million includes 1.75 million voters, according to the government. But exiles would have to return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> to vote under the law, which the opposition is trying to change to allow voting in consulates. As many as half a million Nicaraguans have fled the war and economic chaos in their country, with most settling in neighboring Central American countries and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION>. The Contra statement said the Contra leaders will not return to <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION> until they have successfully concluded talks with the internal opposition aimed at unifying anti-Sandinista groups and settling on a single presidential candidate. The Contras will insist on a `` national dialogue'' to set conditions for February's vote, the statement said. `` With a unified opposition, the candidate should take the initiative to call all Nicaraguans back to support them,'' <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. `` Returning before that would be premature.'' The Contras and the Internal Civic Opposition are meeting to establish such a united front, <PERSON> Sanchez </PERSON> said. Asked how long the unification might take, he said `` we had hoped it would already be done,'' refusing to give a deadline for the talks to end. He said the <ORGANIZATION> Sandinistas </ORGANIZATION> have blocked the negotiations with a series of `` impediments,'' such as denying visas to participants to freely enter and leave <LOCATION> Nicaragua </LOCATION>.
