on House and Senate resolutions.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 As rival troops squared off in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, The <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> administration said Tuesday that <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s senior leaders appeared to have left the capital and urged the 1,440 Americans in the city to get ut themselves. `` It's like the place is closed down,'' said <ORGANIZATION> White </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Marlin </PERSON> <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON>. `` There's been no communication from the leadership. There's no indication who the leadership is.'' At the <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION>, spokeswoman <PERSON> Margaret </PERSON> <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> called the situation in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> `` tense and unsettled.'' She acknowledged there may be dissension within the Chinese armed forces and a <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence source, commenting on the grounds of anonymity said, `` What we're seeing, first, is a political struggle, the outlines of which are very vague. Plus there is a serious division'' within the <ORGANIZATION> Chinese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> leadership. <PERSON> Fitzwater </PERSON> said the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy has been in contact only with mid-level <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> officials but has had `` no contact with the top-level people _ and we've tried. `` The assumption has been that the top-level people have moved out to other locations. We tend to believe it.'' <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON>, meanwhile, referring to the shooting of hundreds of students demonstrating for democracy, told reporters: `` We have reason to believe that all elements of the Army do not support what is taking place. We have no firm evidence of armed clashes.'' The Chinese capital was threatened with civil war as armies loyal to rival political factions were reported battling in the city. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence source said his information was that <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> had refused to move against the students in Tiananmen Square even as <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> elements from <LOCATION> Nanjing </LOCATION> carried out Sunday's bloody attack. `` We're hearing all the reports of shooting between <ORGANIZATION> Army </ORGANIZATION> units, but we have not confirmed that ourselves,'' the source added. An official, speaking on conditition of anonymity, said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> intelligence reports reaching <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> estimated the death toll at 3,000, in line with estimates by diploatic sources in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> but 10 times the <LOCATION> Chinese </LOCATION> government estimate. This official said the reports stressed the toll could go higher. Secretary of State <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> A. </PERSON> <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> <PERSON> III </PERSON> decided to encourage Americans to leave <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> after a long telephone conversation Monday night with <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Lilley </PERSON>, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> ambassador there. <PERSON> Baker </PERSON> was told 50 percent to 75 percent of the employees of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> firms had already decided to leave. Ms. <PERSON> Tutwiler </PERSON> said arrangements were being discussed with <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> to supplement their regular service from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> with charter flights to carry out Americans. But <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Joe </PERSON> <PERSON> Hopkins </PERSON> said in <LOCATION> Chicago </LOCATION> that his airline had no plans to add flights. `` We're just operating our regular schedule'' of three flights a week, he said. Indeed, one <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN