ZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> to repeal the tax law, which forces companies to prove their health benefits are as generous to low-paid workers as they are to executives For procedural reasons, <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> would have needed 60 votes to prevail. <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> called the provision `` unwise, unworkable and just plain unfair.'' Democrats agreed that the tax law needs revamping, but said revoking it would be a mistake. `` Is there any reason we should be favoring management?'' asked <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>. The legislation is aimed at providing extra money for the rest of fiscal 1989, which ends Sept. 30. It contains $ 1.2 billion for veterans programs, $ 892 million for student loans, $ 342 million for the costs of last summer's Western forest fires, and money for efforts including foster care, refugees, the <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Nations </ORGANIZATION>, and food stamps. It also bestows federal money on a host of projects of a less sweeping nature, but championed by various legislators for local consumption. Thus, it contains $ 75 million to rebuild a 26-year-old <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Virginia </LOCATION> radio telescope that collapsed last November, sought by <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Byrd </PERSON>, D-W. Thanks to <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> Minority Leader <PERSON> Bob </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON>, R-Kan., $ 275,000 would be set aside for <ORGANIZATION> Kansas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> State </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> University </ORGANIZATION> to advise farmers on coping with drought Sen. <PERSON> Howard </PERSON> <PERSON> Metzenbaum </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Ohio </LOCATION>, garnered $ 500,000 for engineering work on a lake in <LOCATION> Cincinnati </LOCATION> that has filled with sediment. <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>'s two <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators, <PERSON> Malcolm </PERSON> <PERSON> Wallop </PERSON> and <PERSON> Alan </PERSON> <PERSON> Simpson </PERSON>, got $ 400,000 for a study of last summer's fires at <ORGANIZATION> Yellowstone </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> National </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Park </ORGANIZATION>. In a boon to senators from 39 states, the measure also supplies $ 6.6 million to continue subsidizing air carriers serving small communities. The legislation also carries provisions stating the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION>'s views on an assortment of topics The chamber wants the <ORGANIZATION> Agriculture </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> to buy more apples for the federal school lunch program to help the country's ailing apple industry, thanks to <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> state's two senators, Democrat <PERSON> Brock </PERSON> <PERSON> Adams </PERSON> and Republican <PERSON> Slade </PERSON> <PERSON> Gorton </PERSON>. It wants the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION> to hire more employees in <LOCATION> Honolulu </LOCATION>, in the home state of <ORGANIZATION> Appropriations </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> member Sen. <PERSON> Daniel </PERSON> <PERSON> Inouye </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Hawaii </LOCATION>. And it does n't want Panamanian Gen. <PERSON> Manuel </PERSON> <PERSON> Antonio </PERSON> <PERSON> Noriega </PERSON> to be able to name a new administrator of the <ORGANIZATION> Panama </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Canal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, which by treaty <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION>'s leader is entitled to do. One thing the bill does not have is $ 822 million for various anti-drug programs contained in the $ 3.7 billion version of the legislation the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> passed last month. That discrepancy and others will have to be worked out by negotiators before the bill can be sent to the White House for <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s signature. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, citing the federal deficit, has threatened to veto the measure if it has any money for drug programs. The measure <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> initially proposed was for $ 2.2 billion.
