<SECOND>AM-Federal Dams,0429</SECOND>
<HEAD>Court Bars State Water Flow Regulation</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 An appeals court ruled Tuesday that states can not regulate water flows from federally approved power dams, rejecting arguments from 17 Western states that had sought the authority in order to protect fish. The 9th U.S. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> ruled that the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Regulatory </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION>, a presidentially appointed agency, has exclusive power under federal law to set standards for hydroelectric projects, including water flows needed to protect fish. The ruling, which upheld a 1987 <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION> decision, affects all types of water power projects, including larger utility-owned dams, which periodically must be relicensed. It is primarily important in the <LOCATION> West </LOCATION>, where small hydroelectric projects have flourished since <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> passed a law in 1978 requiring utility companies to buy electricity from those projects when oil prices exceeded certain levels. The states, led by <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>, were supported by several environmental groups, which in written arguments to the court called hydroelectric development `` one of the greatest threats to our nation's free-flowing rivers.'' `` The states tend to be the most knowledgeable, the most sensitive to the resources at stake, and they have a major role to play'' in protecting fish and wildlife, said <PERSON> John </PERSON> <PERSON> Echeverria </PERSON>, general counsel of <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rivers </ORGANIZATION>, which led a half-dozen environmental groups. The federal agency's position was supported by small dam operators and major utility companies, who said state regulation would disrupt hydroelectric development. One such project was the <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> dam, a 3,000-kilowatt project on a tributary of the South Fork of the <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> <LOCATION> River </LOCATION> about 40 miles east of <LOCATION> Sacramento </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION> approved the dam in 1983 and required operators to maintain a flow of 11 cubic feet per second of water into <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> from May to September, and 15 cubic feet per second from October through April, to protect an important trout spawning ground. The <ORGANIZATION> California </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Water </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Resources </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Control </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, at the request of state fish and game officials, set flow standards in 1986 of 30 and 60 cubic feet per second for the same two periods, saying the lesser flows were inadequate to protect the fishery. <LOCATION> Rock </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Creek </LOCATION> officials objected to <ORGANIZATION> FERC </ORGANIZATION>, which ruled in 1987 that it had sole authority to set the flow rates. The dam was completed in 1986 and has operated under the federal standards. The other states supporting <LOCATION> California </LOCATION>'s position were <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Arizona </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Hawaii </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Idaho </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Kansas </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Montana </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nebraska </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Nevada </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Mexico </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> North </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oklahoma </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Oregon </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> South </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Dakota </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Utah </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Wyoming </LOCATION>.
</TEXT>
