<HEAD>Pinochet Warns Against Human Rights Trials Of Military</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By EVA VERGARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 President <PERSON> Augusto </PERSON> <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said the armed forces will not tolerate human rights trials by special courts or the <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> after a civilian government takes over next march. The lame-duck military president also said he will remain as army commander after handing over power to a successor to be elected in national balloting Dec. 14. He said his continuing on an army chief was necessary `` to ensure <LOCATION> Chile </LOCATION>'s institutional organization.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON>'s remarks came Monday at a meeting with <LOCATION> Chilean </LOCATION> women journalists and were carried by local newspapers Tuesday. Under the constitution, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> can stay on as army commander for eight years after stepping down as president. The opposition vehemently opposes that clause, but the 73-year-old <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> has refused to change it. Asked about allegations of human rights violations under his military government, <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said he agrees `` some cases must be dealt with by the courts.'' But he added, `` I can not accept that members of the services be targeted for revenge or that special courts be organized in <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION>.'' He hinted that the future democracy could be threatened if that happens. `` There would be a reaction against that'' from the military, he said, `` and I do n't want to even think what might happen.'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> seized power in a bloody 1973 coup, overthrowing an elected leftist government. Hundreds of leftists later were rounded up. Many were tortured or killed and thousands forced into exile. The <ORGANIZATION> Roman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Catholic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Church </ORGANIZATION> and human rights groups here and abroad have documented the cases of about 750 people who disappeared after being arrested by security agents. Opposition leaders say they are not out for revenge but intend to find the truth about human rights violations and bring those responsible to trial. They insist their aim is to try individuals, not the armed services as such. <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> emphasized that the armed forces have decided to return to barracks and move away from the political arena after 16 years in power. `` Now, I say so long, and It's your problem now,'' he said. `` It's over for me and for the army.'' He said the military was leaving in disappointment, considering the Chilean people as having been `` ungrateful'' to them. He referred to last October's national referendum in which voters overwhelmingly rejected a military proposal extending his term until 1997. The outcome obliged <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> to call the December election. `` We received a country in chaos, and were are leaving a decent country,'' <PERSON> Pinochet </PERSON> said.
