<HEAD>Americans Returning from China Recount Tales of Horror</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-China, Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ANNE BUCKLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
 Americans returning from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> recounted tales of horror, including one man who said he watched as troops opened fire into crowds of students and was shocked because `` I've never seen people mowed down, murdered.'' <PERSON> Merv </PERSON> <PERSON> Lapin </PERSON> of <LOCATION> Vail </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Colo. </LOCATION>, returned from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on Monday, two days after Chinese troops moved in on pro-democracy demonstrators in <LOCATION> Tianmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION>, killing hundreds in the most violent suppression of a popular movement in Communist <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s 40-year history. The stockbroker and amateur hockey coach was on his seventh visit to <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, where he coaches children's hockey in <LOCATION> Manchuria </LOCATION>. He stopped in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> on his way home. `` I saw one soldier go down on his knee _ maybe more than one, things were moving so fast ... and he started firing into the crowd,'' <PERSON> Lapin </PERSON> said. `` There was more than one soldier firing. My guess is there were four, five, six-thousand soldiers. `` They started firing indiscriminately into the students. I saw people falling ... It was chaos at this point. `` I was in a state of shock _ I've never seen people mowed down, murdered,'' <PERSON> Lapin </PERSON> said. `` No one thought this was going to happen. The students were just standing there with locked arms, some five or 10 deep. The feeling I got was that they were surprised. Everyone started running and screaming. `` I saw bodies lying there _ it had to be in the hundreds _ and I saw a tank roll over the bodies.'' At <LOCATION> San </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Franciso </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> on Tuesday, <PERSON> Kathleen </PERSON> <PERSON> Tiedeman </PERSON>, a delegate with the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Joint </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Seminar </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> on </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> Trade </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>, said she tried to get to <LOCATION> Tiananmen </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Square </LOCATION> _ first in a taxi, then on the backs of bicycles pedaled by students. `` We were about two miles from the square when the gunfire started: there was no mistaking it,'' <PERSON> Tiedeman </PERSON> said. `` Then a wave of panic took place. I tripped, and then two thoughts came: One, I'm going to be shot, and two, I'm going to be trampled `` My friend threw himself over me and said: ` Stay down. Do n't move. When we got up, we saw about 20 dead people all around us,'' she said. Passengers arriving at <LOCATION> Los </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Angeles </LOCATION> <LOCATION> International </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION> said they were overjoyed to return to American soil. <PERSON> Carol </PERSON> <PERSON> Young </PERSON> said that from her hotel room she was able to see the tanks approaching the center of the city. `` It was very frightening,'' she said. `` I could see the tanks coming down the street. I could see the guns. I could see the guns raise.'' At <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION> <LOCATION> City </LOCATION>'s <LOCATION> Kennedy </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Airport </LOCATION>, <PERSON> Helaine </PERSON> <PERSON> Harte </PERSON>, 23, of <LOCATION> Livingston </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> N.J. </LOCATION>, who was attending the <ORGANIZATION> Beijing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> College </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Economics </ORGANIZATION>, was among several Americans returning from <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` I was really sorry to see what was going on there,'' she said. `` When the protests started and the demonstrations for democracy, there was lots of joy and goodness but it all turned to disaster this weekend. `` You see tanks in the street, places burning, you hear gunfire _ it's very, very frightening,'' she added. `` I had to leave but I'm sorry that I did. Ms. <PERSON> Harte </PERSON> said she had called the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> Embassy for help in getting to the airport in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, but was told she would have to get there on her own. She finally bribed a taxi driver with a sum she said was more than he normally makes in a year.
