<HEAD>Eds: INSERTS New grafs 5-6, Today, Mana Saeed ... new ceiling, to
UPDATE with comments from UAE minister. Minor editing thruout</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SALLY JACOBSEN</BYLINE>
<UNK>Associated Press Writer_</UNK>
<DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> nations increased their oil production to 21 million barrels a day in May, the highest output so far this year, according to estimates released today. The <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Energy </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Agency </ORGANIZATION> also predicted in its Monthly Oil Market Report that demand for the cartel's oil would rise in the second half of the year to about 20.85 million barrels a day, up from a previous estimate of 20.4 million barrels. The ministers of the 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries were meeting in <LOCATION> Vienna </LOCATION> to set new price and production guidelines for the rest of the year. The ministers opened their formal strategy meeting Monday, then adjourned to hold private bargaining sessions. Estimates of demand for their crude were heavily influencing discussions. Today, <PERSON> Mana </PERSON> <PERSON> Saeed </PERSON> <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON>, oil minister of the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION>, a persistent overproducer in the cartel, said he would like to see <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> boost its daily production to between 20 million and 21 million barrels from the current 18.5 million barrels. <PERSON> Otaiba </PERSON> refused to say how much he'd like of the extra output. The primary issue in the talks, he said, `` is to get everybody within the new umbrella of 20 or 20 plus -LRB- million barrels a day -RRB- as a new ceiling.'' `` There's definitely movement toward an agreement,'' said <LOCATION> Iraq </LOCATION>'s oil chief, <PERSON> Issam </PERSON> <PERSON> Abdul </PERSON> <PERSON> Raheem </PERSON> <PERSON> al-Chalabi </PERSON>, but he did not elaborate No date was set for resumption of their formal talks. Anticipating more demand for their crude, the ministers seemed intent on fixing a higher output ceiling _ of as much as 20 million barrels a day _ for the second half of the year. The ministers also appeared to be leaning toward retaining their benchmark price of $ 18 a barrel. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has recommended discontinuing the target price. The sticking point in their bargaining is how to divide up the extra output among the 13 countries. <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and the <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arab </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Emirates </LOCATION> want a bigger share of any increase. The energy agency's report said <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> production in May rose about 500,000 barrels from April. `` This was primarily the result of higher production in <LOCATION> Kuwait </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Nigeria </LOCATION>, partly offset by a small decline in Iranian and Ecuadorian production,'' it said. Oil futures prices recently have been rising amid speculation about the outcome of the <ORGANIZATION> OPEC </ORGANIZATION> meeting. Other developments also helped drive up energy prices Monday, including the death of <PERSON> Ayatollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Ruhollah </PERSON> <PERSON> Khomeini </PERSON>, the Soviet gas pipeline explosion and turmoil in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. On the <ORGANIZATION> New </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> York </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Mercantile </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Exchange </ORGANIZATION>, the contract for July delivery of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> intermediate, the benchmark grade of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> crude oil, rose 38 cents to $ 20.52 a barrel Monday. Prices of refined products also rose.
