<HEAD>Bentsen to Propose Compromise; Seek Swift Passage of Child Care Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with five grafs to UPDATE with news conference, vote postponed.
Picks up pvs 5th graf, Bentsen's ``children's'' ... A version moving on
general news wires.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> is asking his colleagues to scrap President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>'s child care tax credit proposal in favor of a plan that would help parents pay for their children's day care and health insurance. In a memo sent to committee members Monday and obtained by The <ORGANIZATION> Associated </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Press </ORGANIZATION>, Sen. <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, proposed making the current dependent care tax credit that is available to low - and moderate-income families refundable in advance A new credit _ up to $ 500 a year _ would be created to help pay for health insurance for children under age 19. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> said the proposal would cost the <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> $ 11.6 billion over the next five fiscal years. He said the loss could be offset by added revenue the government will reap when tax credits now extended to troubled financial institutions expire next year and by making permanent the 3 percent federal telephone excise tax. The phone tax is scheduled to drop to 2 percent on Jan. 1, 1990. In the memo, <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> asked committee members to vote on the plan Wednesday. However, because of other <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> business he postponed that action until next week and called off a planned news conference at which he was to outline the legislation. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>'s `` children's initiative'' would replace the $ 2.5 billion tax-credit plan offered by <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> but is not intended to undermine a separate child-care bill sponsored by Sen. <PERSON> Christopher </PERSON> <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Conn </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> aides said <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> wanted his tax-credit package to be passed in conjunction with the final version of <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s bill The Dodd bill would provide federal funds for more child care slots and set minimum federal standards for day care centers. Most Republicans vigorously oppose the regulatory provisions of the Dodd measure and <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> aides said they believed <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> wanted to keep his measure as separate legislation to improve its chances of passage unless a bipartisan agreement is reached on an overall child-care package _ the subject of current negotiations. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, in the memo, said making the existing dependent care credit refundable would provide cash for poor families who owe no taxes, and who therefore would not benefit from a normal credit against tax liability. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, in his child-care bill, also suggested making the existing Dependent Care Tax Credit refundable. The president also proposed a new tax credit of up to $ 1,000 a child, initially for families with incomes of between $ 8,000 and $ 13,000, with the credit phasing in and by 1994 becoming available to familes with incomes of up to $ 20,000. In outlining that proposal to a <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> committee last month, Labor Secretary <PERSON> Elizabeth </PERSON> <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> took a swipe at <PERSON> Dodd </PERSON>'s plan. `` The child care needs of working Americans can best be met by providing assistance to parents, not to providers; through state and local regulations, not federal standards; through community-based and public-private partnerships, not federal bureaucracies; and by parental involvement, not federally mandated procedures.'' Critics of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> plan, while applauding the president's motives, have said that creating a new credit and making parents choose between it and the existing credit would only confuse parents and perhaps cause them to avail themselves of neither Indeed, a <ORGANIZATION> Treasury </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> tax expert at the hearing with Mrs. <PERSON> Dole </PERSON> had trouble explaining the mechanics of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal to the committee. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> made no mention of the <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> proposal in his memo but aides said he believed broader application of the existing credit was a better approach than creating a duplicative approach. The new health insurance credit proposed by <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> would allow families with incomes of $ 12,000 or less to receive a tax credit for up to 50 percent of the cost of insurance premiums for a child under the age of 19. The maximum credit would be $ 500. Families with incomes between $ 12,000 and $ 21,000 would be eligible for a reduced credit, with the exact amount to be determined by income. The health insurance credit, which would become effective in 1991, could be paid out in advance if the taxpayer desired the money up front. <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON> also proposed allocating $ 25 million a year for the next five years, through the <ORGANIZATION> Department </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Health </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Human </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Services </ORGANIZATION>, for a program under which the federal government would pay up to 50 percent of the costs of programs to provide basic health care to uninsured children under age 19 and their families.
</TEXT>
