<HEAD>EEC Reopens Anti-Dumping Process On U.S. Propane Product</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BRUSSELS, Belgium (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 The <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said Tuesday it will consider whether to continue anti-dumping measures against <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> imports of propylene alcohol, a propane-derived product used in making printing ink, paints and cosmetics. The <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers of propylene alcohol are <ORGANIZATION> Union </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Carbide </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION> of <LOCATION> Danbury </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Connecticut </LOCATION>; <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <LOCATION> Kingsport </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Tenn. </LOCATION>, which is part of <ORGANIZATION> Eastman </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Kodak </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>; and <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Celanese </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a subsidiary of <LOCATION> West </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Germany </LOCATION>'s <ORGANIZATION> Hoechst </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> AG </ORGANIZATION>. Current anti-dumping measures against imports of <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> propylene alcohol were first decided in April 1984. They were due to expire last year, but will be kept in force until the new investigation is completed, the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Commission </ORGANIZATION> said. According to a commission statement, the anti-dumping case was reopened at the request of the <ORGANIZATION> European </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Chemical </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Industry </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Federations </ORGANIZATION> -LRB- <ORGANIZATION> Cefic </ORGANIZATION> -RRB-, a Brussels-based group representing more than 80 percent of <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> production of the chemical. <ORGANIZATION> Cefic </ORGANIZATION> has alleged that <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> producers export their product at about 10 percent below their internal market price. According to European producers, <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> production capacity of 92,000 metric tons a year exceeds <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> internal demand by about 65,000 tons. <ORGANIZATION> Cefic </ORGANIZATION> said <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> export of propylene alcohol to the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION> has risen to 14,762 tons in 1988, worth roughly $ 10 million, from 6,758 tons in 1985, even with the anti-dumping measures. Under the current measures, the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> companies have undertaken not to undercut European companies' pricing in the <ORGANIZATION> EEC </ORGANIZATION>.
