<BYLINE>By ALAN FRAM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Democrats and Republicans bickered today over whether to repeal a tax law that businesses find burdensome, as the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> struggled to complete a wide-ranging, $ 3.3 billion spending bill. As the <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> began its third day of debate on the legislation, Sen. <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>, R-Wis., offered an amendment repealing a section of the 1986 tax-revision law that he said has `` wreaked havoc'' on companies because of its complexity and costs Democrats countered with a provision that conceded the tax requirement is `` onerous'' and urged its reworking by <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> later in the year. President <PERSON> Bush </PERSON> first asked <ORGANIZATION> Congress </ORGANIZATION> more than two months ago to provide extra money for this year for several federal agencies. Since then, the measure has grown not only in size but in breadth, attracting an assortment of amendments ranging from <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> policy in <LOCATION> Panama </LOCATION> to work on an <LOCATION> Ohio </LOCATION> lake. <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON>'s amendment revokes a requirement that businesses satisfy a complex test to prove that their health insurance plans are not more generous to upper echelon employees than they are to low-paid workers. Companies have complained that the provision, which took effect this year, has created mounds of paperwork. Small businesses in particular have been unhappy. <PERSON> Kasten </PERSON> called the problem `` the No. 1 domestic issue in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION> today'' in a written statement last week, and his amendment was co-sponsored by at least 13 other <ORGANIZATION> GOP </ORGANIZATION> senators. <PERSON> Bush </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Senate </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Finance </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Lloyd </PERSON> <PERSON> Bentsen </PERSON>, <LOCATION> D-Texas </LOCATION>, and <OR