<UNK>Saudi Arabia Makes New Oil Strike</UNK>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION>, the world's largest oil exporter, has made a new oil find in the <LOCATION> Khurais </LOCATION> region southeast of the capital of <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>, oil industry executives said Tuesday. Officials at the <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION> oil company, reached by telephone from <LOCATION> Bahrain </LOCATION>, confirmed the report but refused to give details about its potential. The company is based in the kingdom's Gulf city of <LOCATION> Dhahran </LOCATION>. The new find results from a large-scale high-technology exploration program launched by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION> in 1986, the company officials said, speaking on condition of anonymity. As part of the program, <ORGANIZATION> Saudi </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aramco </ORGANIZATION> drilled a new wildcat well in the <LOCATION> Khurais </LOCATION> region 125 miles southeast of <LOCATION> Riyadh </LOCATION>. The drillers hit a small amount of oil in a reservoir and had some gas shows. First reports suggested that oil discovered in that region was not in commercial amounts, but <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION> was optimistic about the gas. Sources close to <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION> say the gas discovery was sizeable and commercially viable, but the company officials declined to confirm or deny the report. Saudi Aramco announced this year its proven oil reserves have risen to 252 billion barrels from 169 billion barrels. Its annual report for 1988 speculated that remaining reserves could be as high as 315 billion barrels. <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Arabia </LOCATION> has the world's largest known oil reserves. Almost all are in areas managed by <LOCATION> Saudi </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Aramco </LOCATION>, which has discovered 52 oil fields and one commercial gas field in 55 years of exploration.
