<FIRST>r f AM-TrainingAmerica     06-06 0408</FIRST>
<SECOND>AM-Training America,0423</SECOND>
<HEAD>Report: U.S. Needs More, Better On-the-Job Training</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ARLENE LEVINSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> employers must train workers more and better and reward enhanced skills to remain competitive internationally, according to a study released Tuesday by the <ORGANIZATION> American </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Society </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> for </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Training </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Development </ORGANIZATION>. `` The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> can educate and train employees outside the workplace until it is blue in the face, but if employers do not design institutions and jobs that use and reward learning, all efforts will make little difference,'' the report said. The study was released at the annual meeting here of the 45-year-old <LOCATION> Alexandria </LOCATION>, Va.-based society, which represents nearly 50,000 professionals involved in employer-based training. The group includes managers, administrators, educators and researchers who devise in-house training. Their work ranges from teaching illiterate workers to read, to improving sales and customer service skills, to educating executives in running a company. `` Analysis of the available data and case studies of individual employers leads to the conclusion that employers' current commitments to training and development are probably insufficient,'' the report said. It said that while learning in the workplace can boost individual opportunity and corporate competitiveness, `` learning has a relatively low standing and low frequency in the American workplace.'' Citing federal <ORGANIZATION> Bureau </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Labor </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Statistics </ORGANIZATION> data, the report said 11 percent of <LOCATION> American </LOCATION> workers receive formal training and 14 percent get informal on-the-job training to prepare for jobs. By the year 2000, the report said, 65 percent of all jobs will require some training or education beyond high school, compared with 54 per cent now. The report recommended that: _ Employers set short-term targets of spending 2 percent of payroll on formal training and increasing the proportion of workers tapped for extra training to nearly 15 percent, from 10 percent now The long-term goal should be 4 percent of payroll costs to train 30 percent of employees. _ The government create tax incentives to induce employers to improve the quality of worker training _ Employers and educators join to raise the level of workplace training and education _ Firms establish workplace incentives for advanced training through performance-based selection, appraisal and rewards The study was the second in a month to warn that weak job training was hurting <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> productivity. A two-year <ORGANIZATION> Massachusetts </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institute </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Technology </ORGANIZATION> study called `` Made in <LOCATION> America </LOCATION>'' concluded that national proseprity was undermined by industrial weakness. It recommended that companies offer workers more on-the-job training and learning opportunities to improve productivity.
</TEXT>
