<HEAD>Douglas Aircraft Withdraws 51 People, About-Face From 24 Hours Earlier</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: Leads with decision by aircraft maker to evacuate staff; edits
throughout to conform</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICK GLADSTONE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> became the latest big <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> company to pull expatriate workers from strife-racked <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> today, chartering a plane to withdraw its 51 people from <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION> and two other cities. The move by the division of <ORGANIZATION> McDonnell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Corp. </ORGANIZATION>, a partner in a joint-venture aircraft assembly plant outside <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, was an about-face from the company's position a day earlier when it said business was normal. The company also became one of the first <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses to charter a plane for evacuations and one of the first with big operations outside <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> to withdraw. Up to now most of the evacuees have been from the capital, which has been in turmoil since the weekend when troops killed hundreds of civilians. `` We've changed our situation in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. We decided last night to begin pulling our people out of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> back to <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION>,'' <ORGANIZATION> Douglas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Aircraft </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Donald </PERSON> <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said from company headquarters in <LOCATION> Long </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Beach </LOCATION>, <LOCATION> Calif. </LOCATION> `` The situation apparently has changed overnight.'' <PERSON> Hanson </PERSON> said the company's 43 people based just outside <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, seven people based in the southwest city of <LOCATION> Chengdu </LOCATION> and one representative in the northeast industrial center of <LOCATION> Shenyang </LOCATION> would leave as soon as possible. Many other <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> businesses that had reacted cautiously toward <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s political crisis also have been withdrawing workers from <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> and a growing number are becoming gloomy about the longer-term impact to their investments. `` Now with this random shooting in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> it's no longer fun. Anyone who approaches a window risks his life,'' <PERSON> Jerome </PERSON> <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, an international lawyer who helped pioneer the American business presence in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>, said Monday. `` With respect to our own staff, I think it is time to withdraw for a while,'' said <PERSON> Cohen </PERSON>, whose firm of <PERSON> Paul </PERSON>, <PERSON> Weiss </PERSON>, <PERSON> Rifkind </PERSON>, <ORGANIZATION> Wharton </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Garrison </PERSON> has offices in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>. `` Until this weekend I thought that was unwarranted. But now we have to think of people's safety. <ORGANIZATION> United </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION>, the only <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> carrier to <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION>, was heavily booked on its 400-seat flight out of the capital today, spokeswoman <PERSON> Sara </PERSON> <PERSON> Dornacker </PERSON> said. By early this afternoon the airline had not added any flights, although there were reports the <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> embassy in <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> was trying to charter planes to help evacuate American nationals. Ms. <PERSON> Dornacker </PERSON> said <ORGANIZATION> UAL </ORGANIZATION> was continuing to deliberately delay the Tokyo-Beijing leg of its regular U.S.-to-Beijing flight by 15 hours to avoid an overnight layover in the capital, fearing the airport might close. <ORGANIZATION> Northwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Airlines </ORGANIZATION> spokesman <PERSON> Kevin </PERSON> <PERSON> Whalen </PERSON> said earlier that the airline's <ORGANIZATION> Tokyo-Shanghai </ORGANIZATION> flight also was delayed to minimize ground time in <LOCATION> Shanghai </LOCATION>, `` just because the situation is so fluid there.'' <PERSON> Robert </PERSON> <PERSON> Cox </PERSON>, a senior executive of the international law firm of <ORGANIZATION> Baker </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> & </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> amp </ORGANIZATION>; <PERSON> Mckenzie </PERSON>, said his China-based staffers had left for <LOCATION> Hong </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Kong </LOCATION> because of the concern for personal safety, and `` clients are dealing with the situation there the same as we are.'' `` The implications of this are profound,'' <ORGANIZATION> Cox </ORGANIZATION> said. `` I do n't see how anyone doing business there could n't set those plans in a state of suspension. <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> business reaction to the chaos in <LOCATION> China </LOCATION> is particularly important because American investment is one of the biggest influences on the country's effort to modernize. More than 600 U.S.-Chinese joint ventures have been signed since <LOCATION> Washington </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> Beijing </LOCATION> normalized relations 10 years ago, with American investment there totaling at least $ 3.5 billion. The <LOCATION> United </LOCATION> <LOCATION> States </LOCATION> is one of <LOCATION> China </LOCATION>'s biggest trading partners. `` A political uncertainty and a standoff is one thing. A massacre is another,'' said <PERSON> Martin </PERSON> <PERSON> Weil </PERSON>, a spokesman for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> China </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Council </ORGANIZATION>, a Washington-based organization of American companies. `` Everybody's going to have to factor that in.'' <ORGANIZATION> General </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Electric </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, <ORGANIZATION> International </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Business </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Machines </ORGANIZATION> <ORGAN