<HEAD>Brothers Charged in Leasing Scam</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Two brothers have been indicted on charges of stealing more than $ 1.7 million in equipment leasing schemes involving <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Systems </ORGANIZATION> and <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Trust </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION>, officials said Tuesday. The <LOCATION> Manhattan </LOCATION> district attorney's office said a 17-count indictment charged <PERSON> Tuvia </PERSON> `` Ted'' <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, 27, and <PERSON> Ephraim </PERSON> <PERSON> Stern </PERSON>, 34, of <LOCATION> Brooklyn </LOCATION>, with illegal use of a legal tax-saving device last year. The Sterns sold printing equipment from two companies they owned to <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> so they could generate a cash profit. They then leased back the equipment so they could use it while writing off the lease cost as a business expense, according to the indictment. If the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON> had kept the equipment in the first place, the only financial advantage would have been the annual depreciation for taxes. Such transactions are legal, but the indictment said the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON> sold property to <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> that was `` greatly overvalued and in some instances was owned by others and in some instances did not exist.'' In one case, according to Assistant District Attorney <PERSON> George </PERSON> <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON>, the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON> bought the <ORGANIZATION> Mayflower </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Printing </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Co. </ORGANIZATION> in June 1988 for $ 50,000 and sold it and nonexistent assets to <ORGANIZATION> Bell </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Atlantic </ORGANIZATION> for $ 600,000 a few months later. To keep the scheme going, the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON> allegedly used phony financial statements and invoices and fictitious eople. In another case, the <PERSON> Sterns </PERSON> used their lawyer's bank account to steal $ 265,000 from <ORGANIZATION> Morgan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Guaranty </ORGANIZATION>, <PERSON> Donahue </PERSON> said. The Sterns aface up to 25 years in jail if convicted of the top count of first-degree grand larceny.
