<HEAD>Governor Touts Alaska Tourism, Says Tourists Have Nothing To Fear
From Spill</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RORY MARSHALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SEATTLE (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s governor and tourism officials, fearing that Americans picture their state as a soiled paradise since the biggest oil spill in <LOCATION> U.S. </LOCATION> history, began a damage-control tour Tuesday to promote the vast reaches unaffected by the disaster. `` If you went to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> and if you wanted to see the oil, you would have to go to a pretty substantial expense and a lot of trouble to do so,'' Gov. <PERSON> Steve </PERSON> <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> told a news conference. Tourism is a $ 750 million-a-year industry for <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, and ranks behind only oil and seafood among the state's biggest industries, <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> said. <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> and other <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> officials emphasized that as large as the March 24 spill was, it was virtually lost amid the state's huge unaffected expanses of land and water. <PERSON> Cowpwr </PERSON> said the spill affected only 2 percent of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>'s 6,640 miles of coastline. That included just 5 percent of the shoreline within <LOCATION> Prince </LOCATION> <LOCATION> William </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Sound </LOCATION>, where the tanker <PERSON> Exxon </PERSON> <PERSON> Valdez </PERSON> ran aground and spilled 10.9 million gallons of crude. <PERSON> Thomas </PERSON> <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Dow </PERSON>, president of the <ORGANIZATION> Alaska </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Visitors </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Association </ORGANIZATION>, a tourism industry group, showed slides taken since the spill, portraying untouched beaches within the sound, a cruise ship crossing the sound, and sea lions in the area where the spill drifted. `` There's no hiding from the fact that it's been a tragedy,'' <PERSON> Dow </PERSON> said. `` But for visitors, few if any will see its impacts on these remote areas.'' Officials have no firm projections how many potential visitors may be deterred by the oil spill, but sport-fishing lodge operators have reported inquiries from their customers and some outright reservation cancellations, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. Like commercial fishermen, tour operators and others in tourism will be entitled to compensation from Exxon if they can show damages as a result of the spill, <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. The state spent $ 10.8 million on tourism promotion in 1988, and the <ORGANIZATION> Legislature </ORGANIZATION> budgeted $ 11.4 million for this year. This year's budget is supplemented by $ 4 million from <ORGANIZATION> Exxon </ORGANIZATION>, part of which is financing this week's promotion trip to <LOCATION> Seattle </LOCATION> and <LOCATION> New </LOCATION> <LOCATION> York </LOCATION>, as well as print and television advertising. One of the ads shows a picture of a smiling <PERSON> Marilyn </PERSON> <PERSON> Monroe </PERSON> without her beauty mark. `` Without it, the picture may have changed, but her beauty has n't,'' the ad reads. `` The same is true of <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>.'' In addition, 154,000 copies of a letter from <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> were sent to people who had inquired about visiting <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION>, assuring them the oil spill would not affect their travel plans. Before the spill, <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> tourism officials predicted just over 780,000 people would visit the state this season, its 30th anniversary of statehood. That would have been up from 709,664 in 1988 and would match 1986, the best year ever, when a number of visitors to British <ORGANIZATION> Columbia </ORGANIZATION>'s Expo 86 world's fair included <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> in their tours. Some visitors may be drawn to <LOCATION> Alaska </LOCATION> because of publicity about the spill and the environmental damage it wrought, officials said. Some entrepreneurs may even arrange tours of oil-fouled areas, Dow predicted. `` I think it's probably correct to say we're getting people up there who want to see the oil spill,'' <PERSON> Cowper </PERSON> said. But, he added, `` they're going to have a hard time.''
