<HEAD>Economist: One-Third of Thrift Industry Can't Meet Capital Requirements</HEAD>
<HEAD>Eds: ADDS 6 grafs to UPDATE with Wall comments.</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOHN A. BOLT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>FORT WORTH, Texas (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 Congressional efforts to force the nation's thrifts to meet stringent capital requirements would push almost one-third of the industry into insolvency and keep home mortgage rates above 10 percent, the chief economist for a trade association said Tuesday. <PERSON> James </PERSON> <PERSON> Christian </PERSON>, director of the economics department for the <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Institutions </ORGANIZATION>, told <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> thrift executives that as many as 973 thrifts, with $ 768 billion in assets, would fail to meet requirements that they maintain 3 percent tangible capital. The industry has been pushing for capital requirements, which either include `` goodwill'' _ the amount of net worth above the value of tangible assets _ or a several-year period to transform the goodwill into money. Opponents have objected to including goodwill because it is intangible. Speaking at the 1989 <ORGANIZATION> Texas </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Savings </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> and </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> League </ORGANIZATION> convention, <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> said many lawmakers apparently feel `` more is better and tougher is what they want to do,'' but he said it is a mistake `` if you have to kill a third of the industry in order to get this done the day after tomorrow.'' <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> said more stringent capital requirements would force institutions to shrink, causing them to sell off mortgages, which in turn would tighten the market and keep interest rates high. He predicted home mortgage rates will average 11 percent this year, falling only slightly to 10.6 percent by 1991. But <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> said the 2,000 remaining thrifts that would not be affected by the more stringent requirements `` are plain vanilla housing lenders for the most part, always have been.'' Critics have blamed much of the industry's problems on savings and loans that strayed too far from their roots as home lenders. This year alone regulators have placed more than 200 thrifts under their control awaiting passage of legislation that would provide more than $ 157 billion over the next 10 years to rescue the industry. The <ORGANIZATION> U.S. </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> favors the more stringent capital requirements, but the legislation is not expected to come up for a floor vote before next week as the <ORGANIZATION> House </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Rules </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Committee </ORGANIZATION> sifts through more than 100 amendments. In other forecasts, <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> said the current business expansion, already the nation's longest during peacetime, could continue at moderate levels for up to two years. But for that to happen, he said, the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Reserve </ORGANIZATION> system must stop worrying about inflation. Until recently, the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> has been pushing up interest rates to keep inflation under control. But <PERSON> Christian </PERSON> said world markets are forcing the <ORGANIZATION> Fed </ORGANIZATION> to rethink that strategy through the strength of the dollar. <ORGANIZATION> Christian </ORGANIZATION> said the inflation rate will rise to 4.8 percent this year before falling to 4.0 percent by 1991. Later, <PERSON> M. </PERSON> <PERSON> Danny </PERSON> <PERSON> Wall </PERSON>, chairman of the <ORGANIZATION> Federal </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Home </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Loan </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Bank </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Board </ORGANIZATION>, told the group that figures to be released Wednesday indicate the evaporation of deposits from the nation's thrifts continued to decline in April, a traditionally down month as taxpayers pay Uncle <PERSON> Sam </PERSON>. In April 1988, thrift deposits grew by $ 1.2 billion as investors shifted money from uncertain stock and mutual fund investments. So far this year, however, $ 28.5 billion has been withdrawn from thrifts, including a record $ 10.8 billion in January. Wall also said that a secret survey by the bank board found some <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plan </ORGANIZATION> thrifts not doing enough to sell distressed real estate. Most federal regulators who have visited <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> in recent months have taken pains to reassure local officials that the government will not dump on the market properties acquired through the rescue of hundreds of savings and loans and banks. But Wall told reporters Tuesday the bank board had sent `` shoppers'' into <LOCATION> Texas </LOCATION> and discovered that some of the properties held by institutions recapitalized last year through the <ORGANIZATION> Southwest </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Plan </ORGANIZATION> had not even been listed for sale. Wall suggested that the <LOCATION> Southwest </LOCATION> <LOCATION> Plan </LOCATION> thrifts _ which were created last year through the consolidation and sale of ailing institutions _ may have taken the `` no dumping'' promise too literally.
