<HEAD>Prime Drops Court Appeal Against MAI Basic</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
 <ORGANIZATION> Prime </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Computer </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION> has dropped its appeal to the 1st <LOCATION> U.S </LOCATION>. <ORGANIZATION> Circuit </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Court </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> of </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Appeals </ORGANIZATION> seeking to enjoin <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Basic </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Four </ORGANIZATION> <ORGANIZATION> Inc. </ORGANIZATION>'s unsolicited takeover bid because <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION>'s recent revision of its offer made the appeal irrelevant. `` It no longer made sense to pursue that deal,'' Prime spokesman <PERSON> Joseph </PERSON> <PERSON> Gavaghan </PERSON> said Tuesday. <PERSON> Gavaghan </PERSON> said MAI's offer of $ 19.50 cash per share would actually be $ 14.80 per share on a fully diluted basis and `` does not reflect the intrinsic value of the company.'' Prime is encouraging stockholders to resist MAI's offer, he said. Prime's board of directors postponed the company's annual stockholders meeting from June 14 to July 26 to `` provide for an orderly, active and effective exploration of all financial alternatives,'' officials said in a statement Tuesday. Prime's board has said it is discussing acquisition possibilities with interested parties and is contemplating a possible recapitalization. On Monday, <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> officials said Prime's consideration of other takeover offers was a `` a deliberate attempt to confuse Prime stockholders.'' Last Thursday, <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> lowered its tender offer 50 cents a share because of Prime's projected results in 1989 and 1990. MAI, which is about one-fourth the size of Prime, which is based in the <LOCATION> Boston </LOCATION> suburb of <LOCATION> Natick </LOCATION>, owns about 1.2 million shares of Prime stock. Since it launched its hostile bid in November, 33.3 million shares were tendered under the $ 20 offer, representing nearly 70 percent of the outstanding shares and just under 50 percent of Prime's stock on a fully diluted basis. <PERSON> Gavaghan </PERSON> said Prime's executive council has agreed to meet with <ORGANIZATION> MAI </ORGANIZATION> Chairman <PERSON> Bennett </PERSON> <PERSON> LeBow </PERSON> at an unspecified future date.
